<HEAD>Dozens Hurt when School Buses Overturn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A school bus overturned on a curve and plunged down an embankment Thursday, injuring 60 people returning from a church outing in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, and more than 20 fifth-graders were injured in a school bus crash in <LOCATION> Albion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, authorities said. No one was killed in either accident, and authorities said most injuries apparently were bruises, cuts and broken bones. Police said the bus carrying a group from the <ORGANIZATION> Walnut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Penn. </LOCATION>, was returning from an outing in <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> when it overturned on a sharp curve known in <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shore </LOCATION> as `` Devil's Elbow.'' At least two adults and one child were admitted to a hospital after the 4:45 p.m. accident. Children on the bus appeared to be between the ages of 6 and 12, observers at the scene of the accident said. Twelve ambulances took them, their chaperones and the bus driver to three hospitals. In <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, 58 fifth-graders from <ORGANIZATION> Lowell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> school in <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> and several chaperones were returning from a field trip near <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, when their bus slipped onto a soft shoulder and overturned south of <LOCATION> Albion </LOCATION>. `` The injuries do n't appear to be that serious,'' said <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Voran </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Marshalltown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> and Surgical Center, where at least 20 students were treated in the emergency room.
