<HEAD>Tens of Thousands Protest in South Korean Cities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with students attacking U.S.
Embassy compound. Pickup 4th graf pvs ``Student protesters...'';
SUBS 7th graf pvs ``It was...'' with one graf to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KWJ4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radical students tossed up to five small explosive devices into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy compound after scaling the walls Friday during a demonstration, police said. Police said the devices exploded but did not cause any injuries or damage. Rioters fought police with rocks and firebombs Thursday after the funeral of a dissident student. They attacked a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cultural center and burned an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag in front of City Hall. The protesters demanded that President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>'s government be removed and the 40,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> go home. About five students who climbed over the wall of the embassy in downtown <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> were arrested, police said. Two other students were arrested later when they rushed through the gates of the compound. Eyewitnesses said the devices that exploded appeared to be homemade. Radical students set off similar devices in February whey they briefly seized the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Protesters broke windows and hurled firebombs at the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> during clashes with riot police Thursday in the center of the city. Protesters burned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag as speakers denounced the government following a march Thursday by about 25,000 people to City Hall. When the crowd did not disperse, police fired tear gas from armored vans and about 5,000 riot police attacked. Student protesters fled into nearby streets and hurled firebombs at police that set fire to several shops and part of a subway station. Terrified pedestrian fled, many choking from thick clouds of tear gas. Skirmishes between police and protesters broke out around luxury hotels. Tourists looked on in astonishment or ran for cover. Gasoline bombs set a roof garden ablaze at the <LOCATION> Lotte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION> and fire trucks forced their way through the rioters to reach it. The street protests this week were the worst in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> since last summer, when demonstrations forced the government to agree to elections and democratic reforms. The Yonhap news agency said 32,000 people took part in anti-government protests Thursday at 34 places throughout <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, but its tabulation appeared incomplete. In the southern opposition stronghold of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> alone, about 100,000 people surged into the central district. Tens of thousands clashed with police. Police in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> arrested 22 people during street battles after the funeral of dissident student <PERSON> Cho </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung-man </PERSON>, who committed suicide Sunday in a protest against the government. `` Down with the military dictatorship!'' and `` Drive out the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>!'' the protesters in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> screamed, hurling rocks, bricks and firebombs. Dozens of windows were broken in attacks on City Hall and the nearby <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cultural center. Gasoline bombs burst into flames amid squads of riot police during the struggle for control of the city's main shopping area. While street battles raged in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and elsewhere, <PERSON> Cho </PERSON>'s body was buried at a cemetery in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> after a five-hour procession that included stops for memorial services at his school in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and home in <LOCATION> Chonju </LOCATION>, another southern city. The funeral procession in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, which police did not try to stop, moved through the center of the capital, snarling traffic in the morning rush hour. `` Down with the murder regime!'' marchers shouted as others in white mourning clothes beat drums and cymbals. Singers chanted dirges and students in white performed a ghost dance. `` We will never end our struggle until we destroy <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s regime! one young woman shouted. Protests began Tuesday to honor <PERSON> Cho </PERSON> and mark the eighth anniversary, on Wednesday, of the 1980 <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> uprising in which at least 191 people were killed. In <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, 100,000 people packed a major traffic circle for a rally demanding a full accounting of the uprising. Thousands of riot police fired tear gas, starting hours of street battles. Protesters shouted `` Execute <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo!'' and `` Unite the motherland by driving out <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. imperialists!'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> helped his fellow army general <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON> seize power in 1980 and succeeded him as president in February. Opposition groups in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> say both men should be held responsible for the harsh military suppression of the 1980 revolt.
</TEXT>
