<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire broke out Thursday night at the eight-story downtown headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, knocking out 911 emergency service and forcing evacuation of the building, officials said. At least seven people were taken to hospitals and several others were treated for smoke inhalation at the scene, officials said. Firefighters brought the blaze under control about 9:55 p.m., two hours after it was reported. About 60 people were working in the building, police spokeswoman Sgt. <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulloy </PERSON> said. About 40 prisoners were evacuated from the city jail on the eighth floor of the building and taken to the basement of <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, she said. The city's 911 emergency service was out of order because of the blaze, officials said, but four phone lines were open to the public to reach police in case of emergency. The four-alarm blaze was reported about 7:45 p.m. on the building's fifth floor, said fire department spokesman Capt. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Galetti </PERSON>. The office of Police Chief <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyner </PERSON> is located on the fifth floor. `` There was some redecorating going on in the chief's office, I'm told,'' <PERSON> Galetti </PERSON> said, adding that the blaze was reported by construction workers. floor. Smoke poured from windows of the fifth, sixth and seventh floors, witnesses said, and several firefighters trapped by fire on the fifth floor were rescued by ladder, officials said.
