<HEAD>Car Dealership Sues Golf Course After Errant Swings Damage Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owners of a car dealership that sells expensive sports cars are teed off about their neighbors, a miniature golf course where they say some players take too-hefty swings. Golf balls have been clearing a 30-foot-high net between <LOCATION> Golfland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Porsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motorsport </ORGANIZATION> for years, said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Boswell </PERSON>, the car dealership's general manager. But the last straw, he said, was when a brass putter also flew over the fence and smashed the windshield of a Porsche 911 convertible. The putter, which also scratched a Porsche 928 on the rebound, caused $ 3,000 in damage, <PERSON> Boswell </PERSON> said. As a result, the dealership filed a lawsuit Tuesday against <ORGANIZATION> Golfland </ORGANIZATION> in <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. It asks for unspecified damages, contending <ORGANIZATION> Porsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motorsport </ORGANIZATION> has suffered thousands of dollars in losses because of the errant golfers. The manager on duty at <LOCATION> Golfland </LOCATION> on Wednesday referred phone calls to owner <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON>, who could not be reached for comment. <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Geri </PERSON>, said Wednesday the couple had not seen the lawsuit, but added that they had done everything possible to prevent balls from going onto adjacent property. <PERSON> Boswell </PERSON> believes most of the wayward balls come from a hole where golfers must hit up a ramp to reach the cup. `` They must treat the hole like they're on a driving range,'' he said.
