 A German-language edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda has gone on sale in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. The paper, which appeared on newstands on Wednesday, will have an initial daily circulation of 15,000, <PERSON> Christoph </PERSON> <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>, who heads the company issuing the newspaper in German-speaking countries, was quoted as saying. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Austria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> expects a deficit of $ 590,000 by the end of the year but hopes to break even by the end of 1989. Pravda is to appear daily, but Sunday and Monday editions will be combined. Prospective readers include companies doing business with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> as well as institutions and associations interested in Soviet bloc events.
