<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Elections     05-19 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Elections,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Gain In Parliament, Indicating More Anti-West Militancy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strong gains by radicals in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliamentary elections signal even greater militancy against the West and more state control of the economy Results from the second round of voting Friday confirmed the advantage radicals gained in the first round five weeks earlier. There were reports of violence in some cities during the bitterly contested election. The breakdown of the new 270-seat parliament between the power blocs is not yet known, but announced results show radicals clearly in the ascendancy after a prolonged struggle with conservatives in the leadership. Parliament has had little say in foreign policy, but Western analysts believe the new radical strength will affect foreign relations, conduct of the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and the course of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s fundamentalist Shiite Moslem revolution They feel the radical gains, at a time of increasing political uncertainty and military setbacks, herald a tougher stand against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> accuse <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of aiding <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the war, which began in September 1980. `` The Iranians will likely prosecute the war more vigorously. They're already rethinking their strategy, which was based on attrition,'' <PERSON> Hans-Heino </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> said in an interview from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` But much will depend on how quickly they can improve the economy,'' <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> said. `` This is their first priority. If they can get credit abroad, to get more military hardware as well as alleviate domestic hardship, they will be more aggressive.'' New alliances that have emerged in the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> hierarchy are sure to affect the struggle over who will run the country after the death of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, the 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch. He has named <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein-Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>, 66, as his successor. <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON> has no significant power base, however, and is opposed by such key figures as <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, the parliament speaker, who regularly leads Friday prayers at <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON> is expected to become a figurehead, with real power held by <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and two or three others. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who is allied with the radicals on several issues, scored a personal triumph in the election by winning 1.3 million votes. Other radical winners include <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Salamati </PERSON>, former agriculture minister; <PERSON> Hojatoleslam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kharroubi </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Pilgrimage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> and is believed to have directed riots last year in the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ateqe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sediqi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajai </PERSON>, widow of President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajai </PERSON>. Leftist opponents of the <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> regime assassinated <PERSON> Rajai </PERSON> in 1981. Of 208 incumbents who ran, only about 100 were re-elected to the new Majlis, as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament is known. Its term is four years. The main group of conservative clerics, the <ORGANIZATION> Militant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clergy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, was weakened just before the elections when a radical faction led by <PERSON> Kharroubi </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pilgrimage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> broke away over political and economic issues. Diplomatic sources with contacts in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> said the split was encouraged by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> and the prosecutor-general, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Khoeiniha </PERSON>, a leader of the `` followers of the Imam's line'' who stormed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in November 1979 and held 52 Americans hostage for 444 days. <PERSON> Serajeddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousavi </PERSON>, a cleric who heads the security apparatus, said in the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Kayhan </ORGANIZATION>: `` Being in a state of war and at this sensitive juncture, we must not allow a bunch of obstructionists to waste parliament's time.'' <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> spent years playing referee between the rival factions, but moved clearly to the radical side before the elections. He decreed wider state powers, opening the way for economic reforms that were blocked by the conservative-dominated Council of Guardians. The council can veto legislation it decides is a violation of Islamic tenets. Since the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON> was overthrown in February 1979, the radicals have sought to nationalize industry and trade, distribute land held by wealthy families and liberalize social laws. Conservatives, supported by the merchant class, advocate a more capitalist economy. `` The radicals' success is significant because it gives impetus to their efforts to achieve state control not just of the economy, but the whole revolutionary apparatus,'' <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> said. A major radical figure to emerge recently is Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali-Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, former ambassador to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. Western Intelligence agencies have linked him closely to Shiite extremists in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> who kidnapped Westerners and carried out suicide bomb attacks. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> told <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> in June 1985 after two Americans were kidnapped in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Shortly before that, <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON> lost his right eye and two fingers of his right hand when he opened a booby-trapped parcel in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> claimed the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> sent it. As interior minister, <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON> was in charge of the elections. Several months ago he replaced 20 provincial governors, who are responsible for screening candidates. He became interior minister in August, replacing <PERSON> Ali-Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nategh-Nouri </PERSON>, conservative head of the Hojati Islamic faction. <PERSON> Nategh-Nouri </PERSON> did not win a majority in his <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> district in the first election round April 8, but made it May 13.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanche </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> news editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He has covered <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the region since 1985.
