<HEAD>Secessionists Want To Carve Out Biggest U.S. County In Desert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WRIGHTWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Pines </PERSON> dot snowy peaks outside as <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinard </PERSON> sits in his rustic office in a peach cowboy shirt, crusading to carve away 90 percent of the nation's largest county to create <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. At 18,160 square miles of mostly desert north of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gabriel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> mountains, the new county would still be the nation's largest, bigger than <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> combined. Both it and what remained of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> would have better-focused government if voters agree to a `` divorce'' by passing Measure A, said <PERSON> Pinard </PERSON>, who publishes a local newspaper from this 6,000-foot-high ski resort town. His allies gathered 15,000 signatures to get the issue on the June 7 ballot. If approved by a majority vote, <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> would begin operating after a Board of Supervisors is elected in November. Four-fifths of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s 1.1 million residents are jammed into the far eastern edge of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> megalopolis, and <PERSON> Pinard </PERSON> says they deserve a county government that concentrates on urban woes: air and water pollution, gangs, gridlock. But the 205,000 people in the proposed new county confront other problems. The area encompasses military and Indian preserves, mining regions, wilderness, a slice of <LOCATION> Death </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> resorts and the mountains near <LOCATION> Wrightwood </LOCATION>. `` You come up over the mountains and you have people with an entirely different set of problems,'' said <PERSON> Pinard </PERSON>, who would like to be elected a <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> supervisor. `` We've got snow; they've got gutters and curbs. Residents of such <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> basin cities as <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> are `` just not conscious of our concerns,'' he said. But opponents of the `` divorce'' contend a new, 2,000-square-mile <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> would really be `` <LOCATION> Podunk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' the second-smallest in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, stripped of money and influence. They belittle promises by <PERSON> Pinard </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of more efficient and responsive government, better roads and law enforcement. Opponents say it instead would skirt bankruptcy from the outset, with too little industry for its size. Its far-flung voters would be unlikely to approve bonds to fund a jail, hospitals or other public works; and services would suffer, they contend. `` They say <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> government is too fat and unresponsive, and maybe that's true,'' said <PERSON> Nelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wrightwood </LOCATION>, coordinator of the NO on Mojave committee. `` But I think we should work at changing it before jumping off a cliff.'' A key point of contention is a report by a special governor's commission that found <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> to be economically feasible, with an $ 88,000 surplus on a yearly budget of more than $ 137 million, assuming current service levels The commission, mandated by law after Measure A qualified, sketched a division of assets and liabilities and organization of the new county. It said current <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> employees would be able to work for Mojave with no cuts in pay or benefits. As part of the settlement, it said, the old county would owe the new $ 11.8 million, to be paid in three yearly payments. But late last month, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Supervisors sued, contending the study failed to account for unfunded pension liabilities that would mean the new, smaller <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> would be owed as much as $ 33.6 million by <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> ruled May 11 that he had no authority to invalidate the proposal. The supervisors' appeal will not be heard until after the election. Most of the proposed county now is represented by Supervisor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyner </PERSON>, who cast the sole vote against filing the suit. <PERSON> Joyner </PERSON>, who is running for re-election against a former aide, has not said how he will vote on the measure. If <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> is created, <PERSON> Joyner </PERSON>'s district would be reduced to most of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, including the Big Bear and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arrowhead </LOCATION> resorts, and the <LOCATION> Morongo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> desert area. <PERSON> Pinard </PERSON> said he had believed odds for passage of Measure A were slightly better than 50-50; but with the supervisors' suit, he said, `` I just do n't know _ the chances have to be revised downward.''
