<SECOND>PM-Farewell Party,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Getting Wish Posthumously: A Piano Dropped From The Sky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In his lifetime, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> had a secret wish, an unusual fantasy: He wondered what an airborne piano would sound like crashing to earth. Now, a bit late, his friends will find out. The <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> man was 44 when he died three years ago, leaving an $ 800,000 estate. In his will, <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, whose life was full of adventure and fun-loving behavior, left $ 15,000 to three buddies who were instructed to toss one last party for their departed friend. The professional guitar player told his friends to `` give a party for themselves and as many of my friends as they can find that desire to attend.'' As told by <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s friends, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> native moved to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area in 1972. He sang Delta blues and found time to be a parachutist, pilot, storyteller and business success with six furniture stores. It took three years to straighten out <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s will, and on May 28, hundreds of folks are expected to gather for the memorial celebration. They will indulge Young's strange fantasy _ listening to a 300-pound piano crash to the ground from a hovering helicopter. `` He talked about that all the time,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, 53, a <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> graphic designer who met Young in a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Anselmo </LOCATION> saloon 10 years ago. `` He'd sit here and say, ` <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, we've got to have a piano drop. Can you hear it? ... You take an old upright piano about 1,000 feet in the sky ...''' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> mused over that, and added fondly, `` ... I think he'll be able to hear it.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said a helicopter will drop an inlaid walnut upright from 50 to 100 feet near <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. `` It's an arrogant, outrageous, playful, childish thing to do,'' said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. `` That embodies J.C.'' About four hours after the smash, the celebration will turn to a more sedate mood with food, drink and music in <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION>. Friends said the sendoff fits in with <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s life. He once drove a motorcycle into a bar and ordered a beer with an olive. However, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> was far from a clown. He had a master's degree in mathematics, and often dragged bar patrons into conversations about negative numbers and mind-twisting theorems. His death was as unusual as his life. His body was discovered in his black Cadillac in a ravine below a steep highway near <LOCATION> Stinson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. Authorities said he may have been beaten to death. `` He was full of life and I miss him,'' said real estate broker <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Catlett </PERSON>, who met young in a bar in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1972.
