<FIRST>r a PM-Autos-Future     05-19 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Autos-Future,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automakers' Crash Diets Leading To Lasting Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Big Three automakers are replacing their crash diets of the early'80s with more lasting changes to prepare for challenge of the next decade: overproduction. By 1990 there could be 5.6 million more new cars and trucks than buyers worldwide, according to industry estimates. `` First, obviously, cost-cutting was the major concern ... But in the long term it's the products they're coming out with'' that will determine who survives, said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Having modernized their factories and corporate structures, the Big Three are marshaling their resources with the aim of making American cars that are better engineered and sell like Japanese cars. The dollar's slide against the Japanese yen and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> currencies two years ago has made some imports more expensive and temporarily helped level the playing field for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. So has a new <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> pattern contract that stresses job security over wage increases and gives the companies needed flexibility. The auto industry tumult of the past 15 years _ fuel crises, a recession and the shock of Japanese entry _ has given way to a more stable market where winners and losers no longer are determined by national origin. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, losing $ 1 million a day at the beginning of the decade, has made big adjustments already, closing excess plants and running the rest on overtime while grabbing styling leadership from <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> with a sleek, aerodynamic new lineup. `` People who go into a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> dealership have a car in mind. They say ` I want that Thunderbird, Taurus, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>','' <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> said. `` People are not doing that for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>. ... They're going to a <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> dealer and saying: ` I've got $ 13,000. What can I get?''' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> led <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers in earnings in 1986 and went on to set the world auto industry record with $ 4.6 billion in 1987 profits and again with $ 1.6 billion in earnings in the first quarter of 1988. It also has a comfortable $ 10 billion cash cushion it is saving for a major electronics acquisition. At its annual meeting last week, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> said the second largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker has no intention of giving up its edge and will substantially increase spending on new product development over the next few years. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, under Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, also has switched its focus from trimming costs to investing in new products. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> had been shedding weight gained in its August acquisition of ailing <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. After squeezing more Jeeps out of a former <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> assembly plant in <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> decided to close <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION>'s other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assembly plant, in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, by year's end It also settled its <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> contract five months early, eliminating the chance of a costly strike in September when its factories will be pushing out 1989 models. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy of aggressive pricing to gain market share at the expense of immediate profits has boosted sales during 1988, including a 72 percent jump for Jeeps and a 55 percent increase for minivans. <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, who faces his shareholders Thursday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, already has injected extra money into research and development for new models and advanced engineering this year and plans more. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, which spent $ 50 billion since the early 1980s to modernize or replace its factories, is also channeling resources into new product development, but analysts say it has more problems to solve. The world's largest automaker is barely breaking even on its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car and truck business despite cost-cutting, which may make additional plant closings necessary. Analysts also question Chairman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s pledge to regain lost market share. To move eight points to 45 percent of the market, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> would have to increase sales by at least 1.2 million cars and trucks a year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> lost market share in 1986 to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> as well as to foreign makers. And the field of competitors only grows thicker. <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>, which joined the ranks of Japanese makers with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants, has sold out its <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> plant's production through October. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s huge <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> plant will begin making Camry sedans this summer and a Chrysler-Mitsubishi plant in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> soon will be churning out sporty 1989 models.
