<FIRST>r a PM-EconomicAnxiety     05-19 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economic Anxiety,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Why The Seers Say `Bah, Humbug' To Strong Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for March improved beyond all expectations, many economists and big investors responded with a chorus of `` Bah, humbug.'' Funny they should pan what would seem like fabulous news. But they've done it before and most likely they'll do it again. They responded that way to news of a lower jobless rate, to increases in factory use, even to the dollar's new stability. It is a strange, discomfiting world in which good is bad, happy is sad, up is down, square is round, best is worst, last is first, strong is weak, bottom is peak, rich is poor and less is more. And if the sages are being spooked by the `` good'' news _ news for which they've waited months and which they deemed necessary for economic survival _ it's no wonder they're exaggerating `` bad'' news, of which they've found plenty. Late last year, for instance, the pessimists said consumers would reduce spending, forcing the economy into recession. It did n't happen. Then they said an inventory glut might produce recession in 1988. But the glut disappeared. `` It is ironic that the pessimistic crowd see a boom just as bloated inventories are starting to cool things off,'' said economist <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Yardeni </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> investment firm, who fears neither a boom nor a bust. Throughout, there has been wide disagreements among economists, some of whom believed the biggest threat was from recession, others that inflation would turn out to be the big problem. Whatever the interpretation, however, the conclusion has been the same, i.e., bad news. If the economy expanded it would strain production facilities and produce inflation. Should expansion cease, recession would follow. The dramatic improvement in the nation's trade deficit _ a $ 4 billion reduction to $ 9.7 billion in March _ provides the most vivid example of the syndrome. Nothing economic has been more eagerly awaited in recent months, since a shrinkage of the deficit means <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods, especially manufactured items, are becoming more competitive abroad. In fact, many economists and investors made the latest trade figures the fulcrum of their analyses. When the deficit grew in February, the stock market plunged. Would a gain in March make the market rise? It did n't happen. Once again the news, though opposite to that of February, produced a negative reaction. Both the bond and stock markets interpreted the news as indicative of an economy about to overheat and produce inflation. `` It seems the better things get, the worse they're going to be,'' quipped <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON>, the publisher, who was addressing a business luncheon group shortly after hearing the news. Why the mood? Economists themselves have been asking that question, and most have defended their positions with data and theories that to the layman seem thorough, reasonable and even sagacious. While recognizing that pessimism may be justified _ and that inflation, high interest rates and perhaps recession lie ahead _ some economists believe there is a large psychological element involved. In fact, with so many disproportions and dislocations in the economy _ big budget and trade deficits, uncollectable Third World loans, and the crash of the securities markets in October _ no matter how poor or inaccurate an analysis might be, a negative forecast stands a chance of being correct. There are also the awful memories of the 1970s to contend with. Economists back then could n't believe what was happening _ that inflation and interest rates were not just high but in the double digits. They can not forget. And, finally, anxiety is produced by the very expansion itself. Now in its 66th month, it has lived far beyond the usual lifespan of expansions, and inevitably will turn down. But when? And will inflation or recession end it? <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinemann </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Ladenburg </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thalmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a securities broker-dealer, remains optimistic, at least about inflation. He notes that major inflation indicators rose less in the first quarter of 1988 than in the final quarter of 1987. His forecast contrasts with that of most economists. `` We're convinced that with just a little bit of luck, the expansion could continue into 1991 or 1992,'' he says, adding the caveat: `` However, this will be a respite, not a reprieve. If <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> can not deal with its problems -LRB- mainly the budget deficit -RRB-, we will all have to live with the consequences.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunniff </PERSON> has covered business and economic issues for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1964.
</TEXT>
