<HEAD>Hastings Takes Fighting Image To Impeachment Hearings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hastings-Impeach, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> and his supporters see him as a courageous, outspoken fighter now taking unfair shots from those who can not accept him as the first black federal judge in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, whose impeachment hearing began Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, has been battling bribery and conspiracy charges for the last seven years. But he has remained a popular figure in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s black community, which has held impassioned demonstrations in his support and contributed $ 65,000 to his legal defense. `` He's never been the kind to back down from a fight; he's had to pull himself up from his bootstraps from day one,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Merritt </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> dentist and longtime friend who helped raise funds for <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>. `` Most federal judges are the placating type, but <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> speaks out _ he's a maverick.'' The flamboyant <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> has proclaimed his innocence ever since he was indicted on bribery charges in 1981 and then acquitted two years later. The case did n't end there. Fellow judges accused <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> of obstructing justice and lying under oath, and issued a report recommending his impeachment. `` I'm not going to be impeached and I'm not going to be removed,'' <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` It's pure unadulterated politics.'' <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, in sermon-like speeches around the country, has blasted the secret judicial investigation after his acquittal as a `` witchhunt'' and an unconstitutional `` throwback to Star Chamberism.'' He has suggested his race has had something to do with the effort against him, and said he really angered <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials with his 1981 rulings blocking deportation of Haitian immigrants. Complaints were filed against him in 1984 for his alleged improper political statements, including harsh criticism of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> said his position on the federal bench does not mean he ca n't speak his mind. `` I do n't have any organized effort,'' said <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, who added he has also spent much of his own money. `` It's draining me financially. It's impacting me from an emotional standpoint _ I'm tired from all this mess. His 70-year-old mother <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON>, with whom <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, 51, has shared a <LOCATION> Lauderhill </LOCATION> apartment since his second divorce, said her son would come out of the hearings fine and `` he does n't need me to talk for him.'' The only child of a maid and butler in <LOCATION> Altamonte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, a small town north of <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hastngs </PERSON> earned his law degree at predominantly black <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> A & amp; <ORGANIZATION> M </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, became a civil rights leader, and ran unsuccessfully for office several times. In 1970, he was the first black man to run for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, but failed to win nomination. He returned to his private law practice, where he did much free work in civil rights cases, until 1979, when President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> appointed him to the federal bench.
