<FIRST>r a PM-HospitalCost     05-19 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Cost,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Admission Review Can Cut Hospital Costs 8 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Insurance companies can cut medical expenses 8 percent if they require people to get approval from a review board before being treated in the hospital, says a study published today. Such `` utilization review'' progams are intended to hold down medical expenses by checking to make sure hospitalization is necessary. The study found that the controls save money, although it did not determine whether they have any effect on health. Utilization review programs generally require that hospital admissions be approved by a review panel before or at the time of admission. The study, directed by Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, was published in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and was based on a review of 222 groups of employees and dependents who were covered by a large private insurance company that required utilization review. The study concluded that utilization review reduced hospital admissions by 12 percent and total medical expenditures by 8 percent. For a typical company with 1,000 employees, this could mean saving $ 636,000 over five years, the study said. For a similar company with a high rate of hospital use, the savings could total $ 2.2 million.
</TEXT>
