<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> are split over whether a proposed swap of 92.5 U.S.-owned acres in downtown <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> for 118,000 acres of swampland in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> is fair to taxpayers, but the committee approved the arrangement. `` This is a good deal ... everybody wins,'' says longtime <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Udall </PERSON>, D-Ariz., who helped put the proposal together Strongly disagreeing is Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., an Interior subcommittee chairman who is first in line to eventually succeed <PERSON> Udall </PERSON> as chairman and who normally is aligned with <PERSON> Udall </PERSON> on issues before the panel <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> says the deal could find taxpayers trading the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> acreage for `` a bargain basement price'' because nobody knows just how much the property will be worth when it is rezoned for commercial development. <PERSON> Udall </PERSON> on Wednesday had the clout that normally flows to a chairman, easily winning voice-vote approval for legislation authorizing completion of what <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> says would be the biggest interstate land trade in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. The proposed deal involves the 104-acre site that now houses the <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, a federal facility that is slated to close next month. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> says the property is one of the most valuable undeveloped urban tracts in the West. An <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appraisal values the parcel at $ 122 million. On the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> end are 118,000 acres owned by the <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> family, although <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> says that 4,236 of them are under tidal water and possibly owned by the state of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. This land would be used to enlarge the Big Cypress National Preserve and the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panther refuge in the southwest part of the state, but the government would not own the subsurface mineral rights. The deal worked out by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> congressional delegation values the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> land at $ 45.1 million. The proposal also calls for the <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> family to pay the government $ 34.9 million. Under the plan, the Colliers would get 68 of the 104 acres in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>. The city of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> would be given 20 acres for a park and the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> 11.5 to expand a hospital, with the state of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> possibly getting the other 4.5 acres. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> challenged the appraisal on the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> property, citing a report by the congressional <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> that says the real value of the land wo n't be known until the 68 acres are rezoned for commercial use. By a 36-3 vote, he lost an attempt to amend the bill to delay completion of the deal until after <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> substantially completed the rezoning process, new appraisals were submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> ruled that what the government was getting was equal to what it was trading away. `` My intention is to make this exchange look a little more like a business transaction,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` We owe this to the taxpayers. ... There is no private individual who would get rid of these lands under these circumstances.'' <PERSON> Udall </PERSON> and other supporters argued that the legislation could bring a higher price for the 68 acres because it requires the tract to be offered to the highest bidder once rezoning is completed. Under the plan, the <ORGANIZATION> Colliers </ORGANIZATION> could get the land by matching the high bid. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said, however, that there is little likelihood another buyer could quickly put together the financial package to satisfy the bill's requirement that the buyer pay cash for the property within 30 days of the bidding. Defending the legislation, Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, said that `` it's a good package for what we're all trying to do. Forget the value of the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> land. ... We're not in the moneymaking business.''
