<FIRST>u a AM-Hostages-Petition     05-19 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Petition,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petition Seeks Release of Western Hostages in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A petition organized by a Christian human rights group asks a Shiite Moslem religious leader in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to intercede on behalf of Westerners being held hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, a former captive said Wednesday. The prayerful plea, with 40,000 signatures, was carried out of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this week and is expected to be delivered this weekend to <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, who spent 17 months in captivity. The wording of the petition was carefully worked out in consultation with <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> religious leaders, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said in a telephone interview at his home in <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, 32 miles south of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Reading from a copy of the petition, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said it reads: `` In the name of one merciful God, we the undersigned wish to express to you our concern and prayers for the hostages held captive in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` We also pray for the countless Lebanese held captive in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` As believers in almighty God we have faith that prayer is more powerful than armies or contingents of diplomats. Because of this we respectfully ask you to pray with us and to do whatever you can to intercede on behalf of all these hostages and captives.''' <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> is a Shiite Moslem religious leader associated with the <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or the Party of God, The Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> is the group believed responsible for the kidnapping of Americans, British and other Westerners in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` What makes this so very important is that a story came out Tuesday in which <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> said the only way the hostages can be released is through direct talks with the abductors,'' <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said. It is hoped that <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> can facilitate those talks, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said. A total of 18 Westerners are being held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including nine Americans. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has been held captive longest. He was kidnapped on March 16, 1985. <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, 57, was released by his captors in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Nov. 2, 1986, after being held for 17 months. He was working as the hospital administrator at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> when he was seized on May 28, 1985. <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said the petition specifically asks <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> to `` join us in prayer'' for the safe return home of Anglican church envoy <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waite </PERSON>, who was taken hostage last year while trying to negotiate the release of other Western captives. The petition concludes, `` We share with you the desire to see all people safe and at peace, and we agree with your statement, ` Neither Islam nor Christianity justify kidnapping.''' The petition was organized by Friends in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, a small <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> group based in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, that has worked quietly, but tirelessly for the release of the hostages since 1986, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> asked that the leader of Friends in the West not be named, saying it may endanger his life, or his freedom, in further efforts to free the hostages.
