<FIRST>r w PM-WhiteHouseBooks     05-19 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-White House Books,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Baker Won't Write Book, but Others Have</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> says top <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides have `` at least an implied commitment'' not to write about their intimacy with power. If so, its a commitment as often honored in the breach as in the observance. A quick survey shows that half a dozen people who have held <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s post of White House chief of staff, or its equivalent, have written books about their experience. About the same number have passed up the temptation. At least three of the chiefs of staff who have written books have described tempestuous circumstances surrounding their departures from the White House. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, however, was apparently the first to rush into print while the president he had served was still in office, which partly accounts for the unprecedented furor his book has aroused. `` I do n't think you ought to write those books,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday. `` I think when you take a job like this that there's at least an implied commitment that you're not going to write books like that. If you're in daily, intimate contact with the president in a decision-making process, I think there's an obligation to treat that discreetly and confidentially. `` I do not intend to write a book,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` I think the bloom is off the rose now with the kiss-and-tell books and I very much hope that that's a phenomemon that's going to subside and go away.'' Maybe so, but it's been around for a while. The very first person to hold the title of White House chief of staff, <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, brought out a book about his experiences in 1961, one year after the president he served, <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, left office. Like more recent ones, the book contained direct quotations from the president's conversations, such as one in which <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> told <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> that the maneuverings of one <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> party leader `` looked like pretty slippery business'' to him. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> did not identify the party leader. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> also sprinkled his book with what appear to be direct quotes from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, although he omitted the quotation marks `` out of deference to the office and the man'' except when he was quoting what had appeared elsewhere. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' book, `` Firsthand Report,'' contrasts sharply with <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s in one respect. In the index, it has nine entries for first lady <PERSON> Mamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>. The index to <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s `` For the Record'' has half a column of entries for <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and nine separate headings covering his controversial disclosures of her interest in astrology. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> is one of the two previous chiefs of staff who, like <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, left office under fire _ <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> over his handling of the Iran-Contra affair and <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> over his acceptance of gifts from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> industrialist <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldfine </PERSON>. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, describing his abrupt replacement by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, recounts an angry telephone conversation in which he told <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> he had `` deserved better treatment'' and the president replied only that he was sorry. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, who had a reputation for reticence, wrote that when he handed the president his proposed statement of resignation, <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> `` said that he wanted nobody but me to make this decision and that under the circumstances he thought I had acted wisely.'' In contrast to this low-key account, H.R. <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> wrote a dramatic recital of his dismissal by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> at Camp <PERSON> David </PERSON>, with <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> telling him that the night before he had `` prayed that I would n't wake up in the morning.'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> said he was touched by the president's words, but was hurt to discover after a <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> television interview in 1977 that the president had spoken the same words to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON> in firing him the same day. In fact, he said it was this interview that prompted him, almost four years after leaving the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, to write his book, `` The Ends of Power.'' He said the effect of the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> interview was to `` distort and confuse'' Watergate issues. The most recent chief of staff to break into print was <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, whose 1982 book, `` Crisis,'' dealt with the last year of the Carter presidency. Other books by top <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides include `` A Political Education,'' published in 1972, by <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON>, who was special counsel to President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, and two books about the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration by <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorensen </PERSON>. Both <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodpaster </PERSON>, who took over many of <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' duties, and <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>, who succeeded <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON>, have written books but they did not deal with their White House days.
</TEXT>
