<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union President <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> was recovering well following successful surgery to remove a malignant tumor from inside his skull, a hospital spokeswoman said. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> underwent the operation Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Barrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neurological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelbart </PERSON> said Wednesday. The 61-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> man was recovering well and without complications, but no further information was being released at the request of his family, Ms. <PERSON> Gelbart </PERSON> said. She said that decisions on further treatment would be delayed until next week, `` pending review of all post-operative studies.'' An <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> newspaper reported that <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> was diagnosed as having brain cancer two weeks ago. He was transferred from the <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Barrows </LOCATION> on May 11. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>, who has been the president of the nation's largest union since 1983, relinquished his duties for four months effective May 4 because of health problems. He underwent surgery for a malignant lung tumor in January 1987 in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. The hospital said the malignancy removed Tuesday apparently had spread from the cancer that led to the earlier operation. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>, elected to a five-year term in 1986 as head of the 1.6 million-member union, is scheduled to stand trial July 12 in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court in <LOCATION> Clev