<HEAD>Masters And Johnson Defend Research Before AIDS Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sex therapists <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Masters </PERSON> and <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> say they published their controversial book on AIDS because too little attention was being paid to the potential spread of the disease among heterosexuals. Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> AIDS commission on Wednesday that the authors did not mean to create `` panic in the streets,'' but wanted to `` counteract an earlier absence of openness, of honesty in collaboration'' on the part of government officials. Federal health officials have criticized the book for suggesting AIDS is spreading more rapidly among sexually active heterosexuals than projected by official government estimates. Another criticism is that the Masters-Johnson findings did not go through the `` peer review'' process required for publication in a major medical journal. `` There would have been no way to publish in journals,'' said Masters, citing both the length of the material and what he said is traditional difficulty in getting sex research accepted in such forums. `` Books are the characteristic mode of publishing in the field of sex research, which is our field,'' added Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON>, a long-term associate of the Masters-Johnson team and a co-author of the book `` Crisis: Heterosexual Behavior in the Age of AIDS.'' To commission chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' admonition that there should be `` an element of solidarity, you might say, among the scientific and medical community'' on AIDS, <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON> replied: `` With all due respect ... the process of science is not and has never been served by looking for unanimity of opinion. The process of science has always been served by allowing people to speak on varying interpretations.'' <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON> acknowledged the book's estimate that as many as 3 million Americans may have the virus without knowing it is about twice as high as the official government estimate. But he emphasized that the difference stems from different interpretations of the same raw data available to both government and private analysts. As to controversy over what is often called casual spread of the disease, <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON> said the book carefully distinguishes between theory and saying `` as a practical matter, this is not something you ought to worry about.'' For example, on the question of risk of catching the virus in a restaurant where a waiter or chief has AIDS `` we said in our book, specifically, not unless you have sex or share needles with that person.'' On catching it from a toilet seat? `` We traveled here by public transportation and we all used the toilets in those areas and that should address the practical aspects of the risk,'' said <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON>. `` We do not suggest for a minute that people not use public rest rooms, but we do suggest that if the public place looks to be contaminated with suspicious substances, blood or other materials, we would n't have used that 15 years ago in the time before AIDS and we do n't suspect that anyone would really use that now. `` This is common sense. No one is claiming that the virus jumps off a surface and bites you,'' <PERSON> Kolodny </PERSON> said.
