pickup.
^With AM-Iran-Elections, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian speedboats attacked a Norwegian tanker twice in the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> on Thursday, shipping executives said. It was <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s second foray against neutral vessels in two days in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. The executives identified the tanker as the 55,173-ton <ORGANIZATION> Berge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strand </ORGANIZATION>, an empty liquefied petroleum gas carrier. Its destination in the gulf was not immediately determined. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they did not know what weapons were used against the vessel in the first attack, at 6:30 a.m. -LRB- 10:30 p.m. EDT Wednesday -RRB-. The Berge Strand began sailing to the southern gulf port of <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> for repairs on minor damage. There were no injuries reported. An hour later the speedboats returned and fired four rockets at the ship, injuring one person, the sources said. They said that the Berge Strand developed engine problems after the second raid, but had no further details. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> attacked the Japanese-owned chemical tanker Ace <PERSON> Chemi </PERSON> on Wednesday. A fire started on the 6,730-ton Ace <PERSON> Chemi </PERSON> that forced its Japanese captain and 16 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> crewmen to abandon ship in <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, the gulf's only outlet. All were rescued by salvage tugs, said shipping executives who spoke on condition of anonymity. In the ground war, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Iranian forces killed or wounded 2,000 Iraqi troops and captured more than 10 square miles of northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in an operation that began Tuesday night. It said many Iraqi troops were taken prisoner. There was no comment from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s 32nd convoy of the year was sailing south through the gulf. It included one U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker, the 46,723-ton Gas Prince, escorted by the missile frigate <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>. The Ace <PERSON> Chemi </PERSON> attack was the first by Iranian gunboats on a neutral vessel since April 24. It came one month after a major clash with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval forces in which six Iranian craft were sunk or disabled. It also was the first since the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration began a new policy May 3 that permits <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships to intervene in attacks on commercial vessels on request regardless of what flag they are flying. Iranian officials recently declared their policy of blow-for-blow retaliatory attacks on neutral shipping would continue. The Ace <PERSON> Chemi </PERSON> raid happened 11 miles south of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Larak </LOCATION> island oil terminal as the Panamanian-flagged ship was heading into the gulf, bound for the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> oil port of <LOCATION> Jubail </LOCATION> for a cargo of petrochemicals, the sources said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships were on patrol as usual in the area at the time of the 8 a.m. attack and monitored the tanker's distress call on radio. But the nearest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vessel was 60 miles away, a two-hour sail at top speed, said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has claimed a dozen raids, six of them independently verified, on Iranian tankers and terminals since April 29. The raids seek to strangle oil exports that support <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the 7 -LCB- - year-old gulf war
