<FIRST>r w PM-MXDevelopment     05-19 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MX Development,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci OKs Development of Missile Rail System; Contracts Let</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has awarded two contracts totaling almost $ 329 million to develop a rail-car launching system for the MX nuclear missile, the Pentagon says. The contracts were let after <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> authorized full-scale development of such a ` rail garrison' system. `` As currently configured, the ` rail garrison' system will consist of 50 missiles, based aboard 25 trains with each carrying two missiles,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> statement said. The MX, a 10-warhead, 195,000-pound missile, is now entering the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s inventory as a silo-based weapon. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to allow deployment of 100 of the missiles, but so far only 50 have been authorized. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a bid to obtain approval for the second 50, proposed in December 1986 that a rail version of the missile be produced to improve its survivability in the event of a Soviet attack. His proposal is known as rail garrison because it envisions placing MX missiles on rail cars that would remain inside military bases, or garrisons, until there was a threat of attack. Only then would they scatter across the country on the commercial rail network. Unlike the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> currently does not have any mobile intercontinental missiles. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> contracts are for the construction and testing of the missile-carrying, launch control and security rail cars that will be needed to make the 71-foot missile mobile. A $ 167 million contract was awarded to <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Marine Division in <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to design, develop and test the missile launch car. The second contract, worth $ 161.7 million, was awarded to <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Autonetics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> Division in <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, for the design, development and testing of the launch control system, launch control car and security car. Both contractors will be expected to complete their work by July 1992, the Pentagon said. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has said it expects each train to include two locomotives and six cars _ two missile launch cars with missiles inside; one launch control car; two security cars, and one maintenance car. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has generally endorsed the idea of developing a mobile missile, but is now locked in a debate over whether to produce a rail version of the MX or a much smaller, single-warhead missile known as the Midgetman that could be fired from a truck launcher.
