<TEXT>
 Thousands of people rallied in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> to tell authorities the sentencing of an Azerbaijani man does not address their demands that a neighboring region be annexed, a dissident source said. `` They think the problem goes deeper than sentencing guilty people,'' <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryabokon </PERSON>, an editor of the dissident journal Express-Khronika, said Wednesday. <PERSON> Ryabokon </PERSON> said about 15,000 Armenians rallied in the streets of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital, on Tuesday, a day after <PERSON> Talekh </PERSON> <PERSON> Salekh </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogli </PERSON> <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> was found guilty of premeditated murder and given the maximum sentence of 15 years. It was the first conviction in connection with three days of rioting that broke out in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> on Feb. 28. <PERSON> Ryabokon </PERSON> said there were no arrests by police during Tuesday's protest He said a few thousand people also gathered in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, the major city of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, after <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> was sentenced to stress that they consider the annexation issue still not settled. <PERSON> Ryabokon </PERSON> said his information came from the weekly journal's correspondent in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> Express-Khronika has been distributing information on dissident activities and actions by various ethnic groups in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> since the fall. Armenians began agitating in mid-February for permission to annex the predominantly Armenian <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region from neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Their campaign apparently led to the riots. Thirty-two people _ 26 ethnic Armenians and six ethnic Azerbaijanis _ were killed in the rioting. The Soviet government has refused to permit the annexation. Instead, it has come up with a costly development program for <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> to improve economic and social conditions.
