<HEAD>A Spoonful Of Chowder Helps The Medicine Go Down At Beth Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chief chef at a popular seafood restaurant chain returned to the hospital where he had been a patient recently to perform some corrective surgery of his own. In the kitchen. As the specialist he is, <PERSON> Jean-Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Paimblanc </PERSON> supervised a well-scrubbed staff of more than 100 at <ORGANIZATION> Beth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. A few watched as he made an incision into a cooked fish. `` Perfect,'' said <PERSON> Paimblanc </PERSON>, of Legal Sea Food's restaurants. `` It should taste moist, but not too soft. This is good.'' For Wednesday's lunch and dinner, Paimblanc and two Legal Sea Food employees oversaw preparation of 1,400 meals for patients and staff at the 460-bed hospital. `` It just takes a little attention to make good, fresh meals,'' said <PERSON> Paimblanc </PERSON>. `` Hospitals serve fish sticks when they could get in fresh fish. They serve frozen vegetables when they could buy presliced fresh vegetables. It does n't take much to make a much better meal.'' The items on the menu were identical to those served at <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION>'s six <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> restaurants, including the fish chowder included at President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s inaugural dinner in January 1981. <PERSON> Paimblanc </PERSON> added a newly created low-calorie clam chowder with clams and vegetables. `` With all the studies talking about the benefits of fish and fish oils on health, it seems like hospitals should be talking a closer look at their meals,'' Paimblanc said. `` We'll put the hospitals out of business if people keep eating like this.'' <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Israel </PERSON>'s director of nutritional services, said research is still ongoing on direct correlations between fish oils and lower incidence of cardiac problems. The hospital omitted a reference to fish oil's health benefits from the back of the <LOCATION> Legal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Food </LOCATION> menu used at the hospital. Paimblanc, 54, was recovering from a mild infection 18 months ago when he wandered into the <LOCATION> Beth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> kitchen bored by his meals. He suggested trying his hand at preparing the hospital's food for a day On Wednesday, 250 pounds each of cod and tuna were baked or broiled under the supervision of Paimblanc, who wove his large frame through the crowded kitchen to inspect the meals. During a break in preparing the fish and stirring the chowder, <PERSON> Paimblanc </PERSON> took time out for his own lunch. A corned beef sandwich.
