<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has ordered the state government to use recycled goods and stop buying polystyrene products, an action that won the praise of environmentalists. `` It is time for us to get away from the notion of a throwaway society and to do everything possible to promote use of recycled and recyclable products,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said Wednesday in a statement that aides admitted was printed on nonrecycled paper. The Democratic presidential front-runner signed an executive order to phase out the purchase of polystyrene, whose production has been blamed for harming the Earth's ozone layer. The order came one day after a Canadian researcher warned that a hole in the ozone layer may be developing above the North Pole. Earlier studies identified a seasonal hole over the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pole </LOCATION> in the ozone layer, which protects the Earth from harmful solar radiation. Scientists have attributed the potentially damaging ozone loss to chemical reactions touched off by chlorofluorocarbons, a family of chemicals used in making plastic foam. The foam, known as polystyrene and sold widely under the trade name <PERSON> Styrofoam </PERSON>, was the target of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' order. Under its terms, the state purchasing agent was told to immediately stop buying disposable polystyrene products manufactured with chlorofluorocarbons. As of June 1, the state will stop buying polystyrene products that are not made from recycled materials. State officials said recycled plastic foam is not considered a threat to ozone. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also ordered the state purchasing agent to expand purchases of recycled paper, recycled aluminum and recycled low-grade plastic products such as trash bags. In addition, the state will begin using `` composted soil supplements'' in parks and roadsides wherever compost is available and appropriate. `` What we have here is another example of how economic growth can be combined with a commitment to the environment and high standards of environmental protection,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told reporters at a <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> news conference. On Monday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won praise from environmentalists by joining Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., in calling for an expanded moratorium on exploratory oil drilling off the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coast On Wednesday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said his goal was to boost the recycling industry by expanding the supply of recyclable materials and the market for recycled products. Aides said the state's purchases of paper, aluminum and plastic amount to millions of dollars annually. According to the governor's staff, the state will incur a slightly higher cost for purchases of recycled paper and an increase of 5 percent or more on recycled aluminum. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> earlier banned state purchases of polystyrene, and 11 states have programs to encourage government purchase of recycled materials, according to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> environmental officials. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> lawmakers recently banned the manufacture and sale of foam products made with chlorofluorocarbons in the state starting in 1990. But the packaging industry views the law as symbolic since no such products are made in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shope </PERSON>, of the Environmental Lobby of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, said the new policy puts <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in the forefront of recycling and noted that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has yet to adopt a similar requirement. `` Who knows? Maybe next year that will change,'' she said, referring to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' presidential campaign.
