<HEAD>Soviets Allow Some Japanese Investigators Aboard Burned Ship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet officials today reluctantly allowed Japanese investigators to search a portion of a Soviet passenger ship to determine what caused a fire that killed at least 11 people and injured 35. After 70 minutes of heated negotiations with Soviet consular officials, police agreed to pare down to 15 a team originally consisting of more than 60 investigators. Police also gave in to Soviet demands that the probe be limited to the passenger cabins of the 4,870-ton Priamurye, gutted by a fire on Wednesday. All of the 129 crew members and 295 passengers listed in the ship's registers were Soviet nationals, and all of the dead were passengers. `` I have no idea why they -LRB- the Soviets -RRB- demanded this and I do n't really understand what the problem is with them,'' said <PERSON> Yoshihide </PERSON> <PERSON> Yasuda </PERSON>, a police official in charge of the investigation. `` But the fact remains that our investigations are limited ... and may not be carried out as expected,'' <ORGANIZATION> Yasuda </ORGANIZATION> said at a news briefing. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> Yasuda </ORGANIZATION> said police and firefighters had been through the gutted ship in a preliminary probe, but the Soviets asked them not to enter the engine room. Police had said the fire was discovered in an area above the engine room. It took 18 hours for firefighters to put out the blaze aboard the Priamurye, which was blackened and listing at dock in this port city of western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The investigative team, clad in boots and overalls and equipped with cameras and flashlights, entered the ship at 10:43 a.m. <ORGANIZATION> Yasuda </ORGANIZATION> said the 10 police, three fire department and two Maritime Agency specialists will concentrate on a cluster of cabins on the second deck, one level below the main deck, where nine of the 11 bodies were found. Maritime official <PERSON> Norimasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON>, in charge of emergency measures, said earlier that a cigarette or faulty lighting could have started the fire, which gutted most of the 85-cabin ship registered in <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Osaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials contacted by telephone said 15 of the original 35 injured in the fire remained hospitalized this afternoon. <PERSON> Yasuda </PERSON> described as `` uncooperative'' the attitude of both Soviet consulate officials and ship captain <PERSON> Aleksandr </PERSON> <PERSON> Yerastov </PERSON>. He said there was little likelihood that investigations could be completed prior to the arrival of a Soviet vessel to take back survivors. Soviet crew members, including about 50 who had remained on board the ship overnight despite police objections, began loading food and beverage supplies to prepare to pull out as early as Friday, officials at the site said. The Piramurye pulled into <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> port Tuesday after calling on <LOCATION> Otaru </LOCATION>, Hokkaido May 8 and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> May 12. The vessel was to leave for <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> tonight. Maritime officials said the passengers, many of them in their 20s and early 30s, were visiting <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for sightseeing purposes as part of the Sputnik youth group tour, organized by the Soviet Communist Youth League.
