<SECOND>PM-Drug Busts,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Drug Seizures Made in New York, Florida And Georgia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Undercover agents broke up an alleged conspiracy to funnel 1,000 pounds of cocaine every 48 hours for a month into a swanky <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> summer retreat, in one of three separate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug busts that netted 17 arrests. In other actions Wednesday, Customs agents said a patrol vessel chased down a high-speed boat running without lights in the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION> just before dawn and found more than 2 tons of cocaine aboard. Three <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> men and a <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> national were arrested and their 38-foot boat confiscated, said Customs spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON>. In Mobile, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, federal authorities charged four people, including a West German couple, with possession of 1 -LCB- tons of marijuana and 236 pounds of a substance believed to be hashish oil, with a combined street value of more than $ 20 million. Customs agent <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the drugs were smuggled into the Gulf Coast from a foreign distribution point apparently aboard a 35-foot sailboat. The plot to sell 8 tons of cocaine in the <LOCATION> Hamptons </LOCATION>, a chic beach retreat on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, came to light when undercover agents learned of an attempt to get a plane for flights between <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, officials said. `` This seizure is unbelievable, out of sight,'' said state police Capt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Heesch </PERSON>. `` It has not only put a major dent into the importation of cocaine to <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> but it has more significantly removed the major players.'' The first shipment, which contained 1,200 pounds of cocaine, was seized Tuesday in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> when the plane transporting it lost an engine and had to land, officials said. The plane, which was headed for <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Westhampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, had been under surveillance since leaving <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The pilot, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pekarchik </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, was arrested in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and eight others, including two Colombians, were arrested Wednesday on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. All were charged with conspiracy to import and distribute cocaine. <PERSON> Heesch </PERSON>, head of the special investigations bureau, estimated that the 1,200 pounds of cocaine could have been sold for $ 80 million. Undercover agents infiltrated the plot by arranging for a jet between <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and helping handle the logistics of the smuggling operation, using electronic surveillance throughout the negotiations. Special Customs Agent <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stiffel </PERSON> said the smuggling ring had planned to bring in 1,000 pounds of cocaine every 48 hours for 30 days, stockpile it at various sites on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and sell it in the Hamptons. `` We got them on their first run,'' said <PERSON> Stiffel </PERSON>. `` They were just gearing up so they had enough supplies during the peak sale period of the summer.'' In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, meanwhile, youthful-looking undercover officers posing as high school students made more than 230 drug buys and arrested 171 drug dealers recently, Police Chief <PERSON> Daryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> said Wednesday. Of those arrested in undercover operations at 10 high schools, <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> said 46 were gang members. Of the total arrested, 104 were younger than 18 years old, and of those, 101 were students. Drugs seized by police, mostly high potency marijuana, were valued at about $ 114,330, the chief said.
