<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jurors in the cocaine-smuggling trial of <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> watched a videotape in which the reputed Colombian cocaine lord called drugs a `` revolutionary'' weapon against North American imperialism. The jury were scheduled to return today for their seventh day of deliberations in the 7-month-old trial. On Wednesday, the jury reviewed a tape made by <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> in 1985 when he was a fugitive in the jungles of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, as well as a June 29, 1983, television tape that a clean-cut <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> made when he was running for the Colombian <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. In the jungle tape, <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> said, `` This is about political action and cocaine has become, and marijuana has become, a revolutionary weapon in the struggle against North American imperialism. Stimulants from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> are the Achilles' heel of imperialism.'' However, added <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, who prosecutors say has neo-Nazi views, `` I have never admitted that I have dealt or done any business with drugs.'' On the jungle tape, <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is dressed in a sleeveless T-shirt and sleeveless denim jacket and has long, stringy hair, in sharp contrast to his short hair and business suit image in court. The last time the jury communicated with the court before Wednesday was Saturday, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> denied requests for the testimony of three prosecution witnesses. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> appeared weary in court Wednesday. His brother, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, an economist in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, said he had been able to visit the defendant during deliberations. `` He's very positive, energetic. He's feeling well. He's in a good mood,'' the brother said. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, 38, and co-defendant <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, 57, are charged with conspiring to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, using <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, from 1978 to 1980. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is charged with conspiracy, two counts of importation of cocaine, seven counts of possession of cocaine with intent to distribute and one charge of engaging in a continuing criminal enteprise. If convicted, he could receive life plus 150 years in prison and up to $ 350,000 in fines and forfeiture of his assets in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, is charged with a single conspiracy count and faces up to 15 years in prison and $ 25,000 in fines if convicted.
