the 46,723-ton Gas Prince, escorted by the missile frigate <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>. A fire on the 6,730-ton Ace <PERSON> Chemi </PERSON> forced its Japanese captain and 16 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> crewmen to abandon ship. All were reported rescued by salvage tugs. The raid on the chemical tanker was the first by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> implemented a new policy May 3 that permits <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships to intervene in attacks on commercial vessels on request, regardless of the flag they are flying. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships were unable to respond to the Ace <PERSON> Chemi </PERSON> raid because the closest <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessel was 60 miles away, a two-hour sail, said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sources. The attacks on the Japanese and Norwegian ships occurred about 11 miles south of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s offshore <LOCATION> Larak </LOCATION> oil terminal, where Iraqi warplanes on Saturday devastated the world's largest tanker, the 564,739-ton <ORGANIZATION> Seawise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giant </ORGANIZATION>, and four other ships. The unofficial death toll stood at 34 after Iraqi F-1 Mirage jets streaked into <PERSON> Larak </PERSON> following a 750-mile run down the gulf. The Seawise Giant, chartered by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as a storage ship, had been unloading oil to the Spanish ship <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION>. At <LOCATION> Larak </LOCATION>, tankers pick up oil brought down the gulf by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s fleet of shuttle tankers. <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> has claimed a dozen raids, six of which were independently verified, on Iranian tankers and terminals since April 29. The raids seek to strangle oil exports that support <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s side of the 7 -LCB- - year-old gulf war Iranian officials recently declared that their policy of blow-for-blow retaliatory attacks on neutral shipping would continue, but Wednesday's was the first since April 24. About 350 seamen have been killed and hundreds of others injured in attacks on more than 500 vessels in gulf waterways in the spillover of the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> land war, which began in September 1980. In the ground war, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Iranian forces killed or wounded 2,000 Iraqi troops and captured more than 10 square miles of northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in an operation that began Tuesday night. It said many Iraqi troops were taken prisoner. There was no comment from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>.
