<HEAD>Editor Of Dissident Journal Says Police Shut It Down Through
Seizure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The editor of a well-known Soviet dissident journal said police held him for a week and seized the computer and printer he uses to produce the magazine as well as its archives. <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> security police `` even took all the pictures off the walls,'' <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> told reporters in his <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartment on Wednesday. The editor said that his arrest and detention show that <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s promised reforms have not ended civil rights violations by the state security apparatus. The former political prisoner was arrested May 9 with four other people at a small country house he uses to produce his 11-month-old unofficial magazine, named Glasnost after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policies of more openness in society. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, a literary expert, said the officers had no arrest or search warrants, and a judge convicted him of `` malicous disobedience'' of a police officer and sentenced him to seven days in jail without a proper trial. `` It is a result of the demonstrably sharp deterioration in the situation in the country of people's rights,'' he said. The actions show that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive for democratization of Soviet society and openness has not meant more tolerance of dissent, <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> was released from jail on Monday and the following day tried to visit the house in the village of <LOCATION> Kratkovo </LOCATION>, 25 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Police sealed off the house and prevented him from entering, saying he must prove to a prosecutor he has the right to live there and that his property wo n't be returned until he shows evidence it belongs to him. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said, however, that a prosecutor told him the matter should be taken up with the militia. `` It's not even clear to whom to turn,'' he said. The editors of Glasnost hope to continue publishing, but they are having trouble getting needed equipment and offices. Glasnost was the first privately controlled periodical to be published openly in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Past dissident magazines had been published clandestinely and many of their publishers were arrested. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> was sentenced in 1983 to 10 years in prison for writing for an underground bulletin on human rights. He was pardoned in February 1987. His arrest May 9 came hours before a group seeking to found a political party called the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> planned to meet in his offices. The group met instead at a nearby club to form the party, which seeks to challenge the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s political monopoly. The weekly newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> has accused the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> of seeking to replace socialism with capitalism and called its members `` convinced enemies of our system, the political and economic system of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> calls for multiparty parliamentary democracy, independent trade unions, a new constitution and the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and areas of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> seized in World War II.
