<HEAD>Survivors Describe Death on North America's Highest Peak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of death, climb, other
injuries. ADDS byline. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENALI MEDICAL CAMP, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new expedition led by the first man to conquer <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION> alone in winter ended less than 1,000 feet from the top when one climber apparently froze to death and three others suffered hypothermia. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON>, 31, died early Wednesday at the 19,500-foot level of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s highest peak, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Two other members of the nine-person expedition were evacuated by helicopter. `` We had a beautiful experience turn into a nightmare,'' one exhausted climber, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, said as he clutched a hot cup of tea at <ORGANIZATION> Denali </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camp </ORGANIZATION> at the 14,000-foot level of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION>. `` It's unbelievable that one minute you can be on top of the world, and in the next minute under it,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. The expedition, which began about May 1, was led by veteran guide <PERSON> Vern </PERSON> <PERSON> Tejas </PERSON>, who last March became the first mountaineer to survive a winter climb to <PERSON> McKinley </PERSON>'s 20,320-foot summit. According to accounts from expedition members, <ORGANIZATION> Tejas </ORGANIZATION> called a conference at about 8 p.m. Tuesday, after nearly 10 hours on the trail. They were still more than 1,000 feet below the summit. <ORGANIZATION> Tejas </ORGANIZATION> warned that the approaching night would be bitterly cold. He told them to make individual decisions on whether to continue. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, at 57 the oldest member of the party, said he had intestinal cramps and decided to turn back with another man, <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Tejas </ORGANIZATION> sent assistant guide <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Swider </PERSON> to accompany them to the 17,200-foot camp. The others, led by <ORGANIZATION> Tejas </ORGANIZATION>, went on. Before the trio reached the haven, <PERSON> Swider </PERSON> fell on the steep, rocky terrain. He was saved from certain death only when <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> secured them using an ice ax. `` We all ended up in kind of a blob, hanging on, looking at each other, because the next step was really kind of a big one _ like a couple of thousand feet right off the ridge, going straight down,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. Other climbers saw the fall and went to the rescue. <PERSON> Swider </PERSON>, who had head lacerations and a back injury, and <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> were helped back to camp, where they spent a long night worrying about their companions. The others had it even worse. Some 500 feet below the summit, <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON> began acting irrationally. It remains unclear whether she was ailing from hypothermia or some sort of altitude sickness, but she grew increasingly cold and unresponsive, the climbers said. While others worked desperately to warm her, <ORGANIZATION> Tejas </ORGANIZATION> tried to dig a snow shelter in the icy, rocky terrain, but in a matter of minutes she was dead. `` She was such a strong supporter of <PERSON> Vern </PERSON>'s,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. `` She was practically on the trip because of him'' after hearing him describe his mountain experiences at a talk in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> was assisted down the mountain Wednesday evening by other climbers. He was treated for three frostbitten toes. <PERSON> Swider </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>, 50, of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, who had severely frostbitten feet, were flown off the mountain to a hospital in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. Tejas remained with the rest of the expedition at 17,200 feet. Two reportedly were recovering well from hypothermia. `` I felt like we had the best guide in the world,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. `` He did everything in the world a human being could be expected to do in a dangerous occupation like this.''
