<HEAD>Frat Suspended for Hanging Battered Female Mannequin From Balcony</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fraternity Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLEBURY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of <ORGANIZATION> Middlebury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> suspended a fraternity for hanging a battered female mannequin splattered with red paint from a balcony during a toga party earlier this month. College President <PERSON> Olin </PERSON> <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> on Wednesday accepted the recommendation of the school's community council to ban the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upsilon </ORGANIZATION> fraternity from living in its house next year or functioning as a social organization. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upsilon </ORGANIZATION> also must participate in a sexism awareness course, said college spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Nief </PERSON>. The fraternity was deluged with criticism last week after several students complained about the mannequin used as a decoration at the party. The mannequin's breasts were mutilated and splattered with red paint, and its head and face were bashed in, according to a letter of complaint seven students wrote to <PERSON> Robison </PERSON>. The action was characterized as being sexist and insensitive to violent crimes against women. In a statement, <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> said, `` It is at just such times as this that we recognize how very much our community depends upon a shared acknowledgement of the limits of permissable behavior. `` Our very survival as a community of learning requires both a generous amount of tolerance and a concomitant willingness to insist that there is ... a point beyond which our tolerance can not and must not be stretched,'' <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> said. `` This recent episode has defined, and defined appropriately, such a limit.'' The fraternity called the council's decision too severe. <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, one of the students who complained, said she was pleased that a sexism awareness program would result from the complaint. After the end of the sc