<HEAD>Three Fraternity Members Indicted in Rape Case, Chapter Suspended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf to ADD suspension of Delta Upsilon fraternity in
Vermont.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three fraternity members were indicted in the rape of an 18-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> student who was near death from drinking. A grand jury on Wednesday indicted an <ORGANIZATION> FSU </ORGANIZATION> student, a <ORGANIZATION> Tallahassee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> student and an <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> student on charges stemming from the March 5 incident at the Pi Kappa Alpha house. The students were arrested last month, and are free on bond. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oltarsh </PERSON>, 23, of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, 21, of <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> were charged with sexual battery. <PERSON> Oltarsh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McPharlin </PERSON>, 19, of Plantation were charged with kidnapping to facilitate the commission of a felony. <PERSON> Oltarsh </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FSU </ORGANIZATION> student, was charged with battery in the scrawling of a fraternity symbol and other writing on the woman's leg and with aiding in the possession of alcohol by a person under 21 The indictment alleged that <PERSON> McPharlin </PERSON>, the Auburn student, and <PERSON> Oltarsh </PERSON> carried the victim, who had passed out and was near death from alcohol intoxication, from the <LOCATION> Pi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kappa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alpha </LOCATION> house to a neighboring frat house, where they abandoned her. The victim was hospitalized for treatment of scratches, bruises and abrasions. Following the indictment, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Orians </PERSON>, the fraternity's national executive vice president in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> FSU </ORGANIZATION> chapter had been suspended and that an undetermined number of its members would be expelled The grand jury, which had complained in an interim report that fraternity members had been uncooperative, reiterated the complaint in a final report Wednesday. After the interim report and a university order disbanding the fraternity for five years, a fraternity member stepped forward, the grand jury said. Information from the fraternity member led to two of the arrests, and another frat member who admitted involvement in the incident was granted immunity in exchange for information leading to the third arrest. According to the grand jury, the informant described sexual activities all four had with the woman, and said they dressed her as she sat slumped on the floor. He said they verbally abused her and repeatdly told her they were members of another fraternity and that they were in that fraternity's house, the panel said. The victim admitted she violated the state's drinking age law against consumption by those under 21, but the grand jury urged she not be prosecuted because of the circumstances. The panel recommended that university police monitor areas where there is drinking, and urged <ORGANIZATION> FSU </ORGANIZATION> administrators to establish a mandatory first-semester orientation course on date rape, drug and alcohol abuse, personal safety and the availability of counseling services. University President <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliger </PERSON> thanked the grand jury for its recommendations, and said he had already directed <ORGANIZATION> FSU </ORGANIZATION> officials to take actions requested by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regents </ORGANIZATION>. `` This university has made it clear it will not tolerate conduct which demeans the human spirit,'' <PERSON> Sliger </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, on Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Middlebury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Olin </PERSON> <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> suspended the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upsilon </ORGANIZATION> fraternity for using a female mannequin that had been battered, mutilated and spattered with red paint as a decoration at a toga party. The fraternity was heavily criticized after students complained about the mannequin.
</TEXT>
