<HEAD>Head of Joint Chiefs Says Drug-Trade Assault Would Mean Tradeoffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION> said the armed forces will carry out any anti-drug assignments that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> decides upon, but he warned the practice could compromise civil rights. `` Putting an end to the drug problem would be much broader than our mission,'' Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said at a news conference Wednesday before a luncheon speech to the Economic Club of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. `` I think there are things we can do, primarily identification, surveillance and tracking of people bringing in drugs in illicit fashion,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said. But, he warned, `` to solve the drug problem and still guarantee all Americans the rights and privileges they enjoy today is a difficult thing. ... To truly stop the flow of drugs you would have to increase police powers and do some searches and seizures that are not contemplated today.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week approved a provision giving the military an expanded role in stopping drug smuggling, including new arrest powers for <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers aboard warships that stop suspected drug boats on the high seas. The House has passed a more far-reaching provision, ordering the president to have the military essentially seal off <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders against illegal drug trafficking. The provisions were attached to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s budget, which is being debated on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> also said he did not expect increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military activity in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> would force the exit of its leader, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The admiral said he did not know when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement might end in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. `` I do not see any short-term or long-term end to the Iran-Iraq war,'' he said, adding that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is committed to protecting shipping in the gulf. `` As long as those interests are in jeopardy, we will be there,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said. `` Of course, the government never said it would be a short-term operation.''
