<HEAD>Aquino To Convene Crisis Committee After Court Issues Summons to
Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said she will convene her Cabinet's crisis committee to discuss the implications of a summons a <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> court issued to her ousted predecessor, <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> told reporters on Wednesday that she would convene the committee soon to discuss the summons issued on Tuesday by the anti-graft court, the Sandiganbayan. The summons stems from a $ 2.5 billion lawsuit filed by the <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Good Government to recover some of the $ 10 billion it alleges <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> stole during his 20 years in office. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has barred <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> from returning from Hawaiian exile to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, from which he was forced in a February 1986 popular uprising. Government sources said the committee must study the legal implications of the lawsuit, including whether the summons can be served on <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and if so, whether he has a legal right to return to answer the charges. A source at the anti-graft court said on condition of anonymity that the summons was forwarded to the Department of Foreign Affairs but had not yet been sent on to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. The source said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> could respond in writing within 60 days of receiving the order. Legal sources said it was not clear whether <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> could demand to answer the charges personally in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. On Wednesday, police fired tear gas and smoke bombs to halt a rally and march to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> by protesters demanding that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> be allowed to return for his mother's funeral. Organizers said at least four women and two children were hurt. Police said there were minor injuries to several demonstrators but did not give a figure. About 5,000 demonstrators rallied to urge the government to allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return to attend the funeral of his mother, <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON>, who died May 4. A breakaway group of 2,000 demonstrators, chanting `` If you want trouble, we will give you trouble!'' later marched toward the embassy and were blocked near City Hall by 50 policemen. A police spokesman said the demonstrators were dispersed when they started throwing stones at the officers, who fought back with truncheons and later used tear gas and smoke bombs to disperse the marchers. The marchers later regrouped in the central Bonifacio Square to protest the dispersal.
