<HEAD>Minister Says Indian Troops Will Withdraw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior government minister told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> today that Indian troops battling Tamil rebels in the north and east will withdraw from the island nation. `` The government is very keen to see the Indian peacekeeping troops leave. They are definitely going,'' said <PERSON> Gamini </PERSON> <PERSON> Dissanayake </PERSON>, land and river development minister. <PERSON> Dissanayake </PERSON> said the withdrawal would be in stages but that the date of the pullout has not been discussed yet. He did not elaborate. Indian Defense Minister K.C. Pant is scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> this week to discuss peace proposals with Tamil militants, who have been fighting for a separate homeland since 1983. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> signed a peace accord in July 29, 1987 to end the Tamil separatist war in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s northern and eastern provinces. The accord, which grants some autonomy to the minority Tamils in exchange for a surrender of weapons, has been rejected by the militants. Indian troops landed on July 30, 1987 to disarm the militants and enforce the peace pact, and an estimated 50,000 Indian soldiers are now in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, a regional power, became involved because of its own 60 million ethnic Tamils, who are politically powerful and have close ties with the Sri Lankan Tamils. A senior police official, meanwhile, reported that Sinhalese extremists killed a candidate of the governing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the central <LOCATION> Kandy </LOCATION> district on Wednesday night. The officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified the victim as <PERSON> Jayaratna </PERSON> <PERSON> Heenbanda </PERSON>, who was going to run for the provincial council elections. A 19-year-old student, <PERSON> Aruna </PERSON> <PERSON> Saman </PERSON> <PERSON> Dissanayake </PERSON>, also was killed Wednesday when gunmen shot at another government party candidate, <PERSON> Sella </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayakody </PERSON>, at <LOCATION> Horona </LOCATION> town, just south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Sinhalese extremists also oppose the accord on grounds that it gives too many concessions to the Tamils. They have vowed to kill government officials, politicians and others who support the peace pact. Tamils are 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, most of whom are Sinhalese. Tamils say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who control the government and the military.
