<HEAD>Judge To Hear Arguments For Retrying Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CLARIFY that no decision made to reopen
trial. Pick up 6th graf pvs: `President P.W...' TRIMS thereafter.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge will hear defense arguments next month that the `` Sharpeville Six'' defendants should be spared death for complicity in the mob killing of a black official, court officers said. The black defendants _ five men and a woman _ were scheduled to hang March 18 for their role in the 1984 mob slaying of a black town councilor in <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. However, a stay of execution was granted March 17 in the case, which has attracted international attention and widespread appeals for clemency. <ORGANIZATION> Pretoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> W.J. Human this week gave permission to defense lawyers to present arguments June 6 on why the trial should be reopened. The lawyers say they have evidence that a key state witness was coerced into giving false testimony. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that no decision had been made on whether to reopen the trial. It noted that government prosecutors would be arguing against the application to try the defendants again. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has said he will not intervene in the case. The trial caused debate in part because the six were not convicted of contributing physically to the death of councilor <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON>. Instead, they were convicted under the doctrine of common purpose, which held them responsible because they actively joined the mob. The killing occurred during riots provoked by a rent increase in <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> and neighboring townships. Also Wednesday, police said a former mental patient on Tuesday night killed two officers, including one accused by black squatters of organizing vigilante gangs against them. The 30-year-old white man who killed the officers in a shootout was identified as <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Plooy </PERSON>. He later was killed by police who stormed his house in <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hoek </ORGANIZATION>, a coastal town on the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. One of the slain police officers, Warrant Officer <PERSON> Hendrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON>, was a <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> policeman for 20 years. The white officer usually worked in impoverished black townships and squatter camps east of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. Last year, he was injured in a hand grenade attack in one township. Many blacks said <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> was connected with attacks and factional fighting aimed at intimidating or displacing squatters. <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> has been mentioned frequently in an ongoing court action filed by squatters who were burned out of their shacks in 1986. The plaintiffs said that <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> and other officers either encouraged or condoned an onslaught on the squatter camp by black vigilantes. Some witnesses have testified they saw <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> in a van leading a force of 1,000 vigilantes, and others say they saw him distributing incendiary devices. Scores of people were killed and more than 70,000 burned out of their homes during attacks on the squatters in May and June 1986. <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> said police tried to stop the violence but were unable to move through the densely packed shanties in vehicles and considered it too dangerous to go on foot. Some squatters have banded together to resist attempts to relocate them, and the government considers other squatter communities strongholds of anti-apartheid militants. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
