<HEAD>Deng Urges Leaders to Take Risks, Says Price Increases Necessary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> said today he advises <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leaders not to be afraid to take risks for the sake of progress, and he cited recent price increases as an example. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> made the comment during a two-hour meeting with <PERSON> O </PERSON> <PERSON> Jin </PERSON> <PERSON> U </PERSON>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s Minister of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, who led a military delegation on a five-day visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. The delegation returns to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> Friday. The 83-year-old senior leader went into semi-retirement last fall and has made rare public appearances. The nationally televised evening news showed <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, looking fit and alert, greeting O with a hug and kisses on both cheeks. `` I often tell my colleagues to be brave and not be afraid of risks, because otherwise, no progress will be made,'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> told the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>. He made the statement while talking about drastic price reforms that have raised the prices of four staple foods by as much as 60 percent. The price increases went into effect in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> four days ago, raising the prices of eggs, pork, vegetables and sugar by 28 percent to 60 percent. They created much grumbling among consumers already unhappy about skyrocketing prices. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s current price reform is a bold yet risky action, but the country's leadership is confident of doing a good job,'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> said. He said the price increases are necessary because food prices in the past were kept artificially low through government subsidies. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> said reform of the price of raw materials would follow the rise in food prices. Resolving the price problem is imperative to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic progress and its attainment of the goal of reaching `` developed-country status'' by the middle of the next century, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> reported <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> as saying. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leadership knows every step the country takes involves risks and it could encounter difficulties,'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> said. `` The party and the masses have to understand this is a demanding task.''
