<HEAD>Chrysler Makes Airbags Standard On Six Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has begun installing driver's - side air bags as standard equipment on three of its models and will add them this week to three more, becoming the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker to make air bags Federal safety regulations require increased use of passive restraints, such as air bags, which inflate in event of a collision, or automatic seat belts. Twenty-five percent of 1988 vehicles must have them, 40 percent in 1989 and 100 percent by 1990. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it began installing driver's - side air bags on <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daytona </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> LeBaron coupe and LeBaron convertible models after Beginning Saturday, its large rear-wheel-drive sedans _ <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Fifth Avenue, Dodge Diplomat and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fury </ORGANIZATION> _ will have them. However, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> plans to stop building those three cars at year's end. The No. 3 automaker said it will tout the air bag-equipped models in a two-page advertisement featuring Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> and a drawing showing how the device works. The ad will run in 14 magazines and newspapers next week. The air bags inflate within one-twentieth of a second after electronic sensors detect the beginning of an impact that would be comparable to hitting a wall at 10 miles an hour or faster. The bags, stored in the center of the steering wheel, deflate almost immediately. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> offers motorized automatic lap and shoulder belts on the imported Conquest and <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medallion </ORGANIZATION> and plans to include them on the Dodge Shadow, <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sundance </ORGANIZATION> and Eagle Premier later this year, said spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Houston </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-largest automaker, offers air bags as optional equipment on its <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tempo </ORGANIZATION> and Mercury Topaz compact cars, plans to add more models by 1990 and may include them as standard equipment on one high-end 1989 model. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> uses automatic motorized front seat belts on several models including the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Escort </ORGANIZATION>, one of its top-selling cars. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest automaker, offers the bags as options on the 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Oldsmobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> 88, plans to offer them on an additional car line in 1989 and plans to make them standard equipment on some 1990 models. Automatic front seat belts already are standard on many <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> models.
