Congdon, who never married</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LATROBE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who served time for killing his heiress mother-in-law and her nurse in 1977 has apparently committed suicide, authorities said. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, 54, slit both wrists and bled to death on his living room floor late Tuesday or early Wednesday, according to <LOCATION> Westmoreland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Deputy Coroner <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Musgrove </PERSON>. <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> was convicted in the slayings of <PERSON> Elisabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Congdon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION> and her night nurse, <PERSON> Velma </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietila </PERSON>, 67, in <PERSON> Congdon </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Superior </LOCATION> mansion on June 27, 1977. <PERSON> Musgrove </PERSON> said <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> left three suicide notes. The <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> reported one note said he was innocent of the murders. The newspaper also cited unidentified sources who said <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> recently complained of being unable to get a job in his hometown of <LOCATION> Latrobe </LOCATION> and of being haunted by notoriety from the murders. An agreement nearly five years ago allowed <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> to plead guilty to second-degree murder and he was released on time already served in prison. It came after the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned his 1978 murder conviction, released him from prison and granted him a new trial. Prosecutors and police had contended the slayings were part of a plot by <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON>, to kill her adoptive mother and collect an inheritance of about $ 8.2 million. <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> was later tried and acquitted on similar murder charges. The couple were divorced, according to <PERSON> Musgrove </PERSON>.
