<SECOND>BC-Campaign Abroad,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Newspapers Comment on Bush and Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> bureaus on how the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Editorial writers abroad have begun looking ahead to a race in November between Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Here is some of what they had to say:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ The Guardian of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -LRB- liberal -RRB-: `` Something that has not happened since 1964 may suddenly, unpredictably, be happening again Almost 24 years ago, <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> won <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for the Democrats. No Democratic candidate since has performed that trick. ... And yet, this morning, we not only find Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> leading <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by 10 clear percentage points on nationwide polls, the front-runner in every major area of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>: we also find him 17 points ahead in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` May polls, of course, may be broken reeds in November. ... But, at the very least, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> ought now to be sitting up and taking urgent notice. Our leaders, and those they pay to advise them on diplomatic developments, have until very recently ... tended to assume that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is a foregone conclusion. That was always a little wonky. Today it looks stupid. Try President <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for size.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ The <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- independent -RRB-: `` The American presidency has more often than not been held by dull men, or by men who would have been thought dull were it not for the interesting events in which they were caught up That is perhaps the explanation of the ` bore factor' which is affecting not just <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> but his most likely Democratic opponent, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. This year's campaign is taking place in times of peace and prosperity for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> unmatched in most presidential election years this century. It is difficult for candidates to sound exciting in such times. ... `` Whoever wins, an envious world will eventually make sure that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> becomes _ for a while at least _ less peaceful, and perhaps less prosperous. That is the fate of great countries which are also democracies in a world in which most countries are neither great nor democratic. Either candidate will soon become more exciting than he is at present because _ sadly _ the events will become so. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> should be grateful for these two ` bores' while she can.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ZIMBABWE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION> -LRB- government-controlled -RRB-: `` In comparing Democrats and Republicans the former are more accessible and easier to communicate with American interests are interwoven with the interests of others. At worst the Democrats make Third World countries at least feel they are considered when <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> makes decisions. But Republicans act in ways that fly in the face of accepted diplomatic norms. `` Because of that primary consideration for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> interests, it is highly unlikely that anyone with political ideas such as <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s would ever reach the White House. ... `` Mr. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had no political program when he came in and may not quite understand the differences between the Contras and <ORGANIZATION> Unita </ORGANIZATION> but he went through on the ` make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> the greatest again' ticket `` Yet the Democrats are the lesser of the two evils. Developing countries would certainly be better off with <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. If he appointed a black to the post of secretary of state this would be for the purpose of internal public relations and not for any consideration of black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Developing countries must accept the fact that developed countries are only what they are because we are how we are. Any change in our status will proportinately change theirs. It is this that is drilled into the resident of the White House to always remember. `` We too in developing countries must always remember that.''
</TEXT>
