<HEAD>Former AP Bureau Chief Pat Yale Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRANFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lucius </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Pat </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Yale </PERSON>, who served as a reporter, editor and bureau chief in a 37-year career with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, died of cancer today. He was 79. <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> retired in 1971 as the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> bureau chief. He had held that position since 1965 after serving for 15 years as chief of bureau in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. From 1942 until 1950, he was chief of bureau in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, born Jan. 4, 1909, in <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> and worked on the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> -RRB- Republican-Times and the <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> -RRB- Herald-News before joining <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1934. He was transferred to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1938, serving on the Foreign Desk and as night editor and city editor in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bureau. While in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, he covered the trial in 1949 of Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>, who stabbed to death his wife's lover. <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>'s verbatim reporting of the sometimes racy testimony became a landmark case in AP trial coverage. Some newspaper editors objected to such frank reporting and voiced their opposition at the annual convention of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Managing Editors in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The convention voted overwhelmingly that the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> should continue such reporting and let newspaper editors decide whether to publish it. <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, who lived in <LOCATION> Essex </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>, and three children, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>, a minister in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, and Mrs. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sukosky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Glastonbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
