<HEAD>Fighting Rages On In Southern Beirut With Negotiations On Truce
Deadlocked</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with one man killed today. Pick
up 4th graf pvs: `A police...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and Iranian efforts to end a two-week battle between rival Shiite Moslem militias remained deadlocked today as fighting raged on in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, where foreign hostages are believed held. Police said one man was killed and 10 people were wounded as the pro-Syrian Amal militia, bottled up in <LOCATION> Shiyah </LOCATION>, its last stronghold in the southern slums, traded machine gun fire with the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>. Today's casualties brought the overall toll to 244 killed and 772 wounded since the fighting began May 6 in the 16-square-mile district. The man killed was a bystander who was checking on his damaged apartment, police said. A police spokesman said the fighting has `` settled into exchanges of machine-gun fire,'' as <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, tightens its grip on 90 percent of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The spokesman, who by regulation can not be identified, said most of those wounded today were civilians hit by rooftop <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> snipers. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> on Sunday massed 7,500 troops and 500 tanks and armored vehicles on the southern, western and northern edges of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and its officers said the army was prepared to move in to quell the fighting. However, there was fear that such a move might endanger foreign hostages believed held in the slums. The independent <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> An-Nahar </ORGANIZATION> said, meanwhile, that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was opposed to such a deployment and wants the Syrians to send in only a limited `` disengagement force'' to separate the combatants. <PERSON> An-Nahar </PERSON> said the Iranians also want guarantees that the Syrian force would not seek to disarm <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s third demand, <ORGANIZATION> An-Nahar </ORGANIZATION> reported, is that `` the issue of releasing the hostages be separated from the objectives of the Syrian deployment,'' the paper added without further elaboration. Most of the 18 foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> are believed held by Hezbollah-affiliated zealots based in the southern slums. Acting Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Besharati </PERSON> said on Wednesday that the hostage issue will be `` solved'' once the fighting ends. `` The case of kidnapping -LRB- foreigners -RRB- in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is part of the crisis which <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is passing through. I believe that if we could end the state of war currently prevailing, then definitely the other case would be solved too,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> today, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, said he would talk with Syrian officials in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> to try to help secure the release of the nine American hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The nine include the longest-held foreign hostage, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent. He was seized March 16, 1985. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, who leaves Friday for the Syrian capital, would not detail his plans. He said the trip was prompted by a concern for the safety of the hostages because of the fighting in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, Brig. Gen, <PERSON> Ghazi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenaan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s military intelligence chief in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Besharati </PERSON>'s efforts to arrange a peaceful settlement were not succeeding. The two met for 90 minutes on Wednesday, after which <PERSON> Kenann </PERSON> said: `` We are giving political efforts a chance to solve the problem and end the bleeding in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>.'' The Iranian embassy said <PERSON> Besharati </PERSON> would meet later today with <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON> to `` pursue his efforts.'' <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, the main power broker in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, is <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s main Arab ally in the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. However, it recently has been alarmed by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s efforts to dispute its role in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by trying to dominate the nation's 1.2 million Shiites through <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> has been embroiled in civil war since 1975.
