<HEAD>Panel Would Require Better Information on Home Equity Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted unanimously today to require banks and credit unions to provide more timely and complete information on home equity loans, or second mortgages. Under the bill, passed by voice vote, lenders would have to disclose prior to making a loan the annual interest percentage rate, any fees associated with the loan, a series of warnings about the risks involved and a description of repayment options. Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the committee's consumer affairs subcommittee, said, `` This legislation will provide consumers with important information regarding home equity lines of `` It will enable those consumers to understand fully the conditions of this new form of consumer borrowing,'' said <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>. `` It will make clear to them that they risk the loss of their home in the event of default.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement handed out in the committee room after the bill was approved, said: `` In recent months we have worked with legislators to ensure that the bill preserves the product by providing for creditors' remedies in deteriorating loan situations. `` However, the disclosure and advertising provisions are impractical. They will result in an unnecessary overload of information for consumers, and they will severely limit the creditors' ability to design informative advertisements,'' the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> said. The biggest difference in the measure approved today and the one which came out of the Annunzio subcommittee in February was a provision barring lenders from unilaterally changing terms of the loans, except in some instances. `` Traditionally, in open-end accounts, a lender has reserved the right to change the terms of the loan,'' said Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, chief sponsor. `` However, this provision causes special problems in the home equity area. The high initial fees, the fact that the home is at risk, and the large lines of credit involved, make this unilateral right to change the terms of the loan undesirable in the home equity area.'' A home equity loan disclosure bill has passed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as part of a bigger bank restructuring bill now being considered by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. A committee staffer said proponents wanted a separate bill to pass the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and be sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in case the bank restructuring measure is not approved.
