<SECOND>AM-Farm Scene,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Job Outlook Bright for Most Graduates with Agricultural Degrees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of new college graduates with agricultural degrees is down again this year, but <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials say their job outlook is the brightest in a decade. One official warned Wednesday that the graduates are declining in number and that this could spell problems in critical food and agricultural specialities in the future. `` The demand comes in part from recent advances in agricultural science and technology, and from the need of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agribusiness to improve its position in international marketing,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Despite the good news of greater job demand and record-high starting salaries, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and college officials said the nation's supply of graduates in agriculture majors continues to decline This year, for example, <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> graduated about 500 agriculture majors, down 35 to 40 from 1987, and <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> graduated 225, down from 301 a year ago. But salaries are looking up. At <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, starting salaries of graduates with bachelor's degrees in agriculture are averaging just over $ 20,000 a year. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> estimates starting salaries near $ 19,000 for those with bachelor's degrees, $ 24,000 for those with master's, and $ 34,000 to start for holders of doctoral degrees. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, reported situation is bright for all food science graduates, who will attract starting offers averaging $ 22,000 to $ 36,000. At <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M, agriculture graduates will average $ 17,000 to $ 26,000 to start. <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> says its graduates with bachelor of science degrees will see salary offers running 4 percent to 6 percent above last year's average of $ 20,406. Campus recruitment also has perked up, with many businesses finding a shortage of new graduates to fill current openings. The hottest spots in the job picture, according to college officials, include food science, poultry production, agricultural education, agricultural chemistry and engineering, dairy science, agricultural journalism, entomology, landscape architecture and ornamental horticulture. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said a <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> panel forecasts a `` continuing national shortage'' of 4,000 agriculture and life sciences graduates annually through 1990. Some experts predict the shortage will continue beyond that date and that it will become more significant as good starting salaries and career opportunities draw off bachelor of science graduates who otherwise might obtain master's or doctoral degrees `` To a degree, the laws of supply and demand will no doubt enter into play here, so that more college students, seeing that the agricultural professions offer good career opportunities, will choose an agricultural major,'' <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said. But he added that if college-bound young people fail to see the opportunities in agriculture, then `` the nation may soon face a critical shortage of expertise in the food and agricultural sciences and professions.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers will get a smaller share of what consumers spend on food this year, according to a new <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. The food marketing bill, or the difference between consumer expenditures and the farm value of domestically produced food, is expected to increase 6.6 percent in 1988, compared with a 4.7 percent gain last year. Food marketing includes the costs of transporting, processing, packaging and merchandising food after it leaves the farm. `` While food expenditures will rise 4.8 percent _ about the same as the pace last year _ the farm value of food is expected to decline 1 percent, because of bigger supplies and lower prices for livestock and poultry products,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. During the first quarter, consumer food costs rose 3.1 percent above a year earlier, with much of the increase due to higher prices for fruit, vegetables and fish. Prices for food served in restaurants and fast-food outlets `` rose a little faster than prices for food at home,'' the report said. For all of 1988, food prices are forecast to rise 2 percent to 4 percent from 1987 when they increased 4.1 percent. The report continued to forecast 1988 net cash income of farmers at $ 50 billion to $ 55 billion, down from last year's record of $ 57 billion. Rising production costs and lower federal payments to farmers are factors in this year's decline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World sugar production in 1988-89 is expected to be a record of about 103.9 million metric tons, slightly more than the 103.8 million tons produced in 1987-88, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The latest figures announced Wednesday included revisions from the department's first forecast issued on May 4, which indicated production at 104.1 million metric tons in 1988-89 and last year's output at 103.6 million tons Production in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> _ the largest producer _ was reduced to a 1988-89 forecast of 8.1 million tons from 8.4 million tons indicated earlier this month, the report said. Revisions also were reported for several other countries.
</TEXT>
