<HEAD>Children Get Sick, Officials Suspect Snow Cones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 15 children became sick with an intestinal bacteria, and health officials suspect tainted snow cones. The children, ages 15 months to 12 years, were infected with the bacteria shigella and have symptoms of vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal cramps and fever, said Dr. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Knox </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> health director. The illnesses began May 9, she said. After talking with the children, health officials figured the culprit could be snow cones from delivery trucks that circle <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION> neighborhoods. But Health Department personnel have been unable to find the trucks. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> said no snow cone vendors have obtained the necessary permit to sell the cones. `` These are usually kitchen operations, and they sell the ice and sell the syrup to other people who in turn peddle it around,'' she said.
