<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> today criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for proposing another in-depth look at the nation's drug problem, saying `` We do n't need another study. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s statement that he would n't bargain with drug dealers prompted a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman to say `` he has his ideas on how he's going ... to do things and that's fine. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made a final appearance in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> before heading off to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, both states part of the June 7 primary season finale. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s will be the biggest primary of the season, offering 314 Democratic delegates, with 109 at stake in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spoke with community leaders in a neighborhood marred by drug use and violence. Asked about President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s announcement Wednesday of a new bipartisan study on drugs, he said, `` I do n't think we need another study.'' `` There is no Democratic or Republican or independent way to fight this,'' the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrapped up a seven-day <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> campaign swing on Wednesday and made an anti-drug message his central theme. Campaigning in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, he said that as president, he would n't `` bargain with drug dealers ... whether they are on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or foreign soil.'' Although he repeatedly refused to state his views directly on the administration's attempts to cut a deal with <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who is under indictment on drug charges, his aides said on background that the message was, `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> just would n't make a deal with a guy like <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>.'' At the White House today, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> was drawn into a debate with reporters over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s edging away from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policy. `` I'm saying that he has his ideas on how he's going to want to do things, and that's fine,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` If you want to drive a wedge between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the vice president, forget it.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' only remaining rival, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, suggested that racist comments by `` irresponsible public leaders'' helped create the climate for an alleged assassination plot against him. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, campaigning in <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, was asked about this week's arrest of a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> couple accused of plotting to kill him. <PERSON> Londell </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON>, were also charged with threatening an informant and possessing an automatic rifle. Papers filed in federal court indicated <PERSON> Londell </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> told an informer he was a member of The Order and other white supremacist groups, and that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> should be killed. But lawyers for the couple said each denied belonging to a white supremacist group, and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said no evidence had been found that the pair belonged to The Order. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> initially downplayed word of the arrests, saying, `` I can not just focus on the two people arrested in St. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON>.'' But later he told reporters: `` The climat