be nothing less than a modern D-day,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The delegate race is over on the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> side _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> mathematically clinched the nomination last month in the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary. On the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> side, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has dramatically widened his delegate lead in recent weeks. By the latest <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> count, he has 1,643 to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 974. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign has written to <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, complaining that under the delegate-selection process `` the vote of the people is distorted.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has long maintained that the support of so-called `` super delegates'' _ party and elective officials who have a vote at the convention _ should be roughly in line with the popular vote. But under party rules, the super delegates are not bound to follow primary results in their states. The letter to <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, signed by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign chief <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> adviser <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauntroy </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>'s delegate to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, urged the party chairman to consider the `` moral and political questions'' raised by the rules. A copy of the letter, dated Tuesday, was sent to the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> camp. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, however, said he did not believe <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would mount a challenge to delegates at the Democratic convention. `` I do n't think we are going to have a fight with Mr. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, who a