<HEAD>Senate Proposal Would Modify Vietnam-Era Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The War Powers Act, a Vietnam-era law that has been the focus of a long-running fight between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, would be overhauled by a proposal introduced Thursday in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our goal is to make the statute more workable,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, a sponsor of the reform Commenting about the existing act, <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said, `` Frankly, if I were president, I would thumb my nose at this legislation. The War Powers Act has never really worked.'' The law was enacted in 1973, over the veto of President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, who argued that it was an unconstitutional restriction on his authority. That is the same position taken by all three subsequent presidents. The law requires a report from the president when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel are sent to situations of `` imminent hostilities.'' Under some circumstances, those troops must be withdrawn after 60 days or 90 days, unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> specifically votes to authorize them to remain. The new proposal would let the troops remain for an unspecified length of time unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> votes to remove them. It also creates a group of 18 senior congressional leaders who would regularly meet with the president to discuss national security matters. `` Presidents have not consulted adequately with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> prior to making decisions to involve the nation in a situation where hostilities are certain, imminent or probable,'' said <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, arguing that the new 18-member group would change that. The congressional leadership group could trigger the war powers law by introducing a resolution to either authorize the troops to remain or to order them withdrawn. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he believes the change is a good idea because the current law `` has never worked very well.'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said he does n't know whether President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will back the change. `` It will be up to the administration to look at this and see if they can support it,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, explaining that administration approval was not sought by the group of legislators who drafted the plan. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said, `` I would hope the administration wo n't veto this.'' He said action is likely later this year by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said that `` the War Powers Act is a good example of the limited ability of human beings to predict future events.'' `` It was written for the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, and has been difficult to apply to current situation of small, brief military clashes or terrorist situations. The most recent dispute over the War Powers Act involves <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> policy of reflagging 11 Kuwaiti-owned tankers and protecting them with <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels have also been authorized to aid neutral merchant vesels which seek help. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has refused to invoke the law, even though there have been four separate clashes between the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has debated trying to invoke the law, but has been unable to agree on whether that should be done. Last year, 115 legislators went to federal court and filed suit, seeking an order directing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to invoke the law. But the suit was thrown out of court and the legislators are now appealing that ruling. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said the law was `` well intentioned, but it has not worked. We have spent countless hours proposing, filibustering, and debating measures to invoke a law _ rather than assessing the wisdom of the policy that prompted the deployment of forces.'' Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` there's an old saying that if something is n't broke, do n't fix Well, the War Powers Act is broken and it should be fixed.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said the law `` encourages confrontation rather than consultation between the presidents and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. When forces are introduced, the debate in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is frequently on procedure rather than policy.'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said many of the problems in the current law arise because `` every president resents a diminuation in his power.'' The law was approved in November 1973 despite the veto by <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 284-135 to override <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s veto while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote was 75-18. Backers of the law argued that it was needed because <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> policies were usurping the congressional right to declare war Since the law was enacted, presidents have formally submitted reports on a dozen occasions, although they have rarely cited the section of the law which triggers the 60-day time period for a congressional vote.
</TEXT>
