<HEAD>State Officials Strip License from Dentist Who Never Went to
School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cura </PERSON> was, by many accounts, a gentle dentist. But he gave up his license three weeks ago, when officials learned he never went to dental school. <PERSON> Cura </PERSON>, 46, was trained in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> as a dental technician and easily passed <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s dental exam seven years ago, his lawyer, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Braxton </PERSON>, said. He treated more than 3,500 patients. `` He learned a lot of techniques in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Braxton </PERSON> said. `` He just watched, observed and started reading a lot of books.'' Doctors praised him as highly competent, and patients said he was generous and had a knack for putting them at ease and getting rid of pain. State licensing officials alleged that <PERSON> Cura </PERSON> forged transcripts indicating he had attended the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Havana </ORGANIZATION> 1958-63 and had received a doctor's degree in dental surgery. They said <PERSON> Cura </PERSON> actually was a high school student in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> from 1958-60. `` We were absolutely thunderstruck and flabbergasted,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Altamonte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> dentist who chairs the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dentistry </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cura </PERSON> told state officials he plans to go dental school, but the board last month rejected his request for a license suspension until he graduated. State officials said Wednesday no decision has been made on criminal charges. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON>, general counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reguation </ORGANIZATION>, said he wished <PERSON> Cura </PERSON> would go to dental school because he did a good job. <PERSON> Cura </PERSON>'s undoing was person who wrote anonymously to the department, saying that on a visit to <PERSON> Cura </PERSON>'s office, he noticed no degrees on the walls and began to investigate. `` I am asking you for all the innocent people that put their lives in his hands on a daily basis and trust him wth surgery without even imagining that he has never had university studies and does not know what he is doing,'' the letter said. <PERSON> Cura </PERSON> could n't be reached, but <PERSON> Braxton </PERSON> said he was contrite. `` I'd say remorseful is a very good word,'' the lawyer said. `` He comitted a wrong, there's no question about it.''
