<HEAD>House Panel Approves Bill Requiring Full Disclosure on Home Equity
Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday unanimously approved legislation requiring lenders to make full disclosure on home equity loans. The bill also is designed to put an end to the use of unfair contract provisions and misleading advertisements. <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, said the measure `` contains the kind of disclosures that will enable a consumer to make a reasoned judgment with the full understanding of what lies down the road.'' The legislation, he said, assures that the consumer will not be surprised by unilateral changes in terms after the contract is in force. `` The legislation is a major protection against consumers being duped by misleading claims and falling into financial traps that could lead to loss of a home,'' <ORGANIZATION> St </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germain </ORGANIZATION> said. The bill requires banks and credit unions to disclose important information about the terms and conditions of the loan, such as the various repayment options, with the application and before fees are required. Current law allows lenders to withhold disclosures until the consumer is about to sign on the dotted line. Lenders also would be required to tell the consumer about all fees which may charged in connection with the loan and whether or not the terms disclosred are guaranteed to remain in effect for a specific period of time. The full committee amended the measure that came out of the consumer affairs subcommittee on Feb. 24 by making more stringent a provision prohibiting lenders from unilaterally changing the terms of the contract after it has been signed, except in narrow circumstances. The bill also limits lenders from calling in the loan before the due date, except in narrow circumstances, and requires lenders offering variable interest rate programs to use an index which is outside their control and is publicly available The consumer also is protected from misleading statements or half-truths in advertisements. If an ad tells of a super-low, short-term rate, it will also have to display, in equal prominence, what the normal rate would be. All ads will have disclose the hidden cost such as fees and points. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gainer </PERSON>, representing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` Lenders have insisted on one-sided contracts which allow them to change the terms at any time after the borrower has signed on the dotted line. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has corrected this inequity by prohibiting the lender from altering the terms after the contract has been signed by both parties.'' <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Meier </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` These loans can be land mines for some consumers. The House bill will give consumers the information they need to keep in a financial safety zone.'' Home equity loans _ a line of credit available to borrowers who provide their homes as collateral _ have grown quite popular in recent years, especially since the federal tax law that went into effect last year still makes the interest on them tax deductible in most cases. Consumer groups report that home equity lending doubled between 1986 and 1987 from $ 40 billion to $ 80 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has passed a less stringent measure as part of a bigger bank restructuring bill which is now before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. A committee aide said proponents wanted a separate bill in case the restructing bill gets bogged down. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the trade group had worked with legislators `` to ensure that the bill preserves the product by providing for creditors' remedies in deteriorating loan situations. `` However, the disclosure and advertising provisions are impractical,'' said the statement. `` They will result in an unnecessary overload of information for consumers, and they will severely limit the creditors' ability to design informative advertisements.''
</TEXT>
