<HEAD>Bush Must Define Himself Without Undermining Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a painfully slow ballet, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is delicately stepping away from <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Each step is carefully choreographed as the cautious <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice president tries to define what he would do as president _ without undermining or angering the president. The Republican nominee-to-be can not win without convincing Americans he is his own man. But he can not break with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> dramatically, for that would shatter <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s hold on the conservative foundation of his bid for the White House. And <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does want to be identified with low unemployment, continuing prosperity and a declining trade deficit _ all current conditions the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration brags about. But he is falling in the polls against <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, in part because he has failed thus far to paint for the voters a vivid picture of what he would do as president. As New Jersey Gov. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> said Thursday, `` <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is a very popular man, but nobody wants a clone.'' The White House appeared to ease the way for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> when spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` He has his ideas on how he's going to want to do things, and that's fine.'' A weeklong trip through the West demonstrated graphically the easy and the hard choices <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must make in the next six months to try to put together a winning coalition in the fall. In the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> hit hard on protecting the environment, proclaiming that the government must do more. He did n't directly criticize the environmental record of the administration, but he did break cleanly with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on one issue Monday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would act to stop the sources of acid rain, while the administration just wants to study the problem more. This was an easy one for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, for the environment is close to a motherhood issue. No one is against clean air and clean water, even though there are disagreements on how to achieve those goals. And acid rain is not a burning issue for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, nor is it one that is central to the basic <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> constituencies. The hard choices for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> come in packages like the administration's dealings with Panamanian strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> indicted <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> for involvement in drug-running, but the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is thinking of dropping the indictments if <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> will give up power. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first reaction was to say that talking about sensitive matters is a mistake. Of course, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> was talking _ albeit carefully _ about the negotiations. Next the vice president said he wanted <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> out of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, leaving the impression perhaps, that a deal dropping the charges was all right. Then, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> tried yet another formulation with yet a different emphasis. He said Friday in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, he wanted <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> `` brought to justice.'' That meant he was against dropping the indictment, right? <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would n't say and neither would aides. It was a precisely vague phrase, for bringing someone into court is only one meaning of `` justice.'' This careful wording did n't draw the attention <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted and thus did n't deal with the problem. At every stop, reporters shouted questions to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> heir-apparent on <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would smile and just say nothing. Wednesday brought yet another effort. `` Drug dealers are domestic terrorists, killing kids and cops and they should be treated as such,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said at the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>. `` I wo n't bargain with terrorists and I wo n't bargain with drug dealers either, whether they are on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or foreign soil. He did n't say <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. And aides were quick to say he was not talking about the current situation, only what he would do in the future. Now there was no doubt that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted to leave the impression that he simply would not cut a plea-bargaining deal with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. To say it clearly would have been critical of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and a step into the middle of a mess <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would like to avoid as much as possible. So <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> tried to say it without saying it. But the problem is a simple one _ it does not answer the basic question: What does <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> think of the proposed deal? So the questions will continue, as long as <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is on the front pages. Likewise with the scandals swirling around Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has refused to comment and so he faces questioning almost every day on whether or not he thinks <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> should resign. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides will talk privately about the need for the vice president to step away from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> himself is the one arguing the time is not yet ripe for clear and definitive moves. The problem for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, as an aide once said, is that he is the Velcro candidate _ everything sticks to him. To win in the fall, that must change for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.
