<FIRST>r i AM-KingTut     05-19 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King Tut,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeology Student Finds King Tut Hoard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A student rediscovered a forgotten hoard of grain, dried fruit, spices and insects from the 3,300-year-old tomb of the Egyptian King Tutankhamun, archaeologists said Thursday. `` It obviously is extremely important archaelogically because it's a very large amount of material,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeology </ORGANIZATION>. `` Very little work has been done on material of this period in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, and I understand that some of the species which have been identified are, in fact, the earliest occurrences,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said at a news conference. Most of the discovery consists of the food placed in Tutankhamun's tomb to sustain him on his journey to the afterlife. Scientists said the material is well preserved and could provide best evidence to date of the diet and lifestyle of the Egyptians at the time of <PERSON> Tutankhamun </PERSON>'s death in 1323 B.C. For more than 50 years, the hoard has lain undisturbed in 30 cardboard boxes in a musty storeroom at the Royal Botanical Gardens. The specimens were sent in 1932 by <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, the British archaeologist who discovered <PERSON> Tutankhamun </PERSON>'s treasure-laden tomb in the Valleys of the <ORGANIZATION> Kings </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, in 1922. They were to have been cataloged by the botanist <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boodle </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Boodle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> both died in the 1930s before the work could be completed, and the specimens were stored in boxes labeled `` From Ancient <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>.'' In February of this year, the material was turned over to a French graduate student at the archaelogical institute, 23-year-old <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutundjian </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Vartavan </PERSON>, for research leading to a master's degree in archaeobotany, the institute's speciality. He recognized notations on the boxes as those of <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, providing the first clue that they might be from Tutankhamun's tomb Scientific analysis confirmed his theory and eventually fragments were matched with photographs taken by <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. `` It all fit in. It was beyond coincidence,'' said archaeobotanist <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillmann </PERSON>, who supervised the student's work. <PERSON> Tutundjian </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Vartavan </PERSON> did not attend the news conference. Professor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, director of the archaeology institute's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION>, said the announcement was delayed until it had completed scientific analysis `` We were anxious to announce it as soon as possible, lest it should leak out, but we felt we had to keep it under wraps as long as possible, so that we could get as much work accomplished as we could,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. He acknowledged that one reason for the secrecy was concern that the Egyptian government might demand possession before the institute had completed its analysis. Last week, the institute informed the <ORGANIZATION> Egyptian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> about the discovery and offered to return the material. As of Thursday, the institute had received no reply, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. The hoard includes fragments of funeral wreaths and more than five pounds of seeds, fruits and spices placed in Tutankhamun's tomb, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said Among identified species are emmer wheat for making bread on the journey, barley for brewing beer, a large quantity of watermelon seeds to chew on, coriander, fenugreek, black cumin, sesame seeds, two kinds of juniper berries, grapes and a datelike fruit known as a jujube. The grains, fruits and seeds were intended as raw materials that figurines known as shawabtis found in the tomb would cultivate into food needed by the `` ka'' _ one of the king's souls _ in the afterlife, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a specialist in insects, said the remains of thousands of beetles also had been identified. The foods were to sustain the boy king through eternity, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said, `` but the insects got through first and had a pretty good crack at them.'' The find represents only a fraction of the food buried in the tomb. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said the remainder is in 110 to 120 original wicker baskets and several pottery jars in the <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Dokki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>.
