congressional hearing. Picks up 10th graf pvs, With the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-ranking <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official on Thursday criticized plans by retreating Soviet forces to leave up to $ 1 billion in equipment and facilities for the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government, and reaffirmed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intention to continue backing the Afghan rebels. `` There have been indications that we have picked up that the intention of the Soviets to turn over equipment and facilities will be on a fairly large scale,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON>, undersecretary of state for political affairs. `` We've heard estimates ranging from a half a billion to $ 1 billion worth of equipment and, or, installations and facilities,'' he added. `` That does n't strike me as a demonstration of tremendous restraint.'' He was referring to statements by Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, the Soviet commander in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, that the value of Soviet bases and equipment left behind after the withdrawal would be 600 million rubles, the equivalent of $ 1 billion. During negotiations that led to the Soviet agreement in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to withdraw its estimated 115,000 Red Army troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials proposed a mutual phase-out of superpower military assistance to the Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government and U.S.-supported mujahadeen. The Soviets rejected the offer, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> kept its promise on the table, saying it would match Soviet restraint with `` symmetrical'' reductions in aid to the mujahadeen. Otherwise, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support to the rebels would continue. <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> said on Thursday, `` I would recall, simply, what we said at the time we signed the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement: that we retain the right to support our friends. We will exercise the right in the event the Soviets continue to supply equipment to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. And we'll have practical ways of accomplishing that purpose. <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> made the comments to reporters while outlining various regional issues President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are likely to discuss at their <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit, May 29-June 2. He declined to predict whether <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would ask <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to help ease the Soviet withdrawal by advising the mujahadeen to refrain from harassing <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> forces. As the first Soviet unit crossed into its homeland on Wednesday, there were reports that guerrilla attacks were continuing. `` The position we've taken on that has been generally that a prompt timetable would be one which is more likely to elicit cooperation from the mujahadeen.'' <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> said. Beyond that, the best way to protect withdrawing forces from attack is to make `` local arrangements'' with guerrilla groups, he said. On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, meanwhile, the Afghan accord was criticized as betrayal of the resistance and an invitation to chaos and civil war. With the superpowers continuing the arms flow, `` What's to prevent a continuing series of civil wars?'' Rep. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>, D-Mass., said at a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Asian and <LOCATION> Pacfic </LOCATION> affairs `` My fear is we are going to see a continung inferno in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> that in time will lead to some kind of Soviet presence unacceptable to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, also said he was concerned about the `` apparent contradiction'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> vowing to halt `` interference'' in Afghan affairs while at the same time reserving the right to aid the rival factions. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON>, R-Ind., declared his `` disgust'' that `` our <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> with its appeasement policy has settled for half a loaf ... There is no substitute for victory and they -LRB- Afghan resistance -RRB- were well on their way to victory. We stopped them short of it.'' With the removal of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> as the No. 1 issue on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s list of regional confrontations with the Soviets, more attention is likely to be given at the summit to conflicts in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> said he was optimistic about the prospects for progress in resolving conflicts in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, in part because of what he termed `` quite successful'' talks recently among officials from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeking a formula under which all Cuban troops _ estimated at up to 45,000 _ would be withdrawn from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would turn over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to an independent government. <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is hopeful that the Soviets will use their influence with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, but he expressed concern that a reported increase in the number of Cubans in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> might set back the process. To lay the groundwork for discussion of the issues at the summit, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> on Thursday winding up talks with a Soviet deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamishin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> reiterated administration views that the regional issue most ripe for settlement is the restoration of a neutral <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, which is controlled by an estimated 120,000 Vietnamese troops. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, which is beset by major economic problems, has stated its intention to withdraw its forces in the early 1990s. `` The principal things we would like to see from the Soviets here are that they press <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> to accelerate the timetable for their withdrawal,'' the official said. He also said the Soviets should talk directly with <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, who represents the anti-Vietnamese factions.
