<DATELINE>ROME, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new exhibit deals with a product that comes from cows, but to many lawmakers it's just plain pork: The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> of Cheese opened Thursday. Sen. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Larraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> was scheduled to preside over the ribbon cutting for perhaps the state's most notorious pork-barrel project. The museum was developed with the help of money tucked into the state budget at <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON>'s request. The $ 425,000 museum received $ 175,000 over the past three years from the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s pork barrel, with the rest of the cost coming mainly from local sources in this central <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> community The museum is housed in the former Weeks and Merry Cheese Factory, which shipped cheese to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> a century ago. The building was moved from nearby <LOCATION> Verona </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> here, a re-creation of a mid-19th century Erie Canal community. Cheese-making tools and equipment, including curd knives, cheese forms and a cheese press, were collected from barns and old cheese factories across the state. While almost everyone else calls it pork barrel spending, legislators and Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> refer to the allocations such as the ones to the museum as `` member items'' or `` legislative initiatives.'' The items, proposed by individual legislators, are reviewed by the state budget division but in general do n't get the kind of scrutiny that major spending items do. <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON>, who admits that `` the Cheese Museum sounded kind of funny the first time I heard it, too,'' said the project makes `` good economic sense'' for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, which lost more than 50 percent of its manufacturing jobs in the last decade. `` The people of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> have experienced three years of being the brunt of everybody's joke and recurring stories about pork barrel spending,'' said <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON>, a Syracuse Democrat. `` The cheese musem is something of which they are enormously proud,'' she said. She added that she hopes the publicity `` can be turned into an advertising plus for the tourist industry being developed by <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>.'' Meanwhile, `` cheese museum'' continues to be synonymous with `` pork barrel'' and the brunt of jokes in the state capital, <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>. Even <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> got a few guffaws Wednesday when asked why he was n't attending the ceremony `` I gave -LRB- scheduling aide <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Belinsky </PERSON> some beef when I found out I was going to be in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> instead of the cheese museum,'' said <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, who will be watching his chief of staff, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Crotty </PERSON>, receive an award from a citizens' group. `` It was a close call, the cheese museum or <PERSON> Crotty </PERSON>.''
