<FIRST>r i AM-Right-Left     05-19 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Right-Left,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baseball Players Prompt Suggestion that Right-handers Live Longer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A study of lifespans of baseball players leads two doctors to suggest that right-handed people may live slightly longer than left-handers. In a letter published Thursday in the science magazine Nature, they said they studied The Baseball Encyclopedia and found that right-handers averaged a lifespan of 64.64 years, compared with 63.97 years for left-handers. The letter was signed by <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Halpern </PERSON> of the psychology department of <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Coren </PERSON> of the psychology department of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>. They said their study covered 1,472 right-handers and 236 left-handers, and excluded players who batted with one hand and threw with the other. No discrepancies appeared until after age 33. After that, about 2 percent more right-handers than left-handers survive at each following five-year period, the researchers said. They said the study gave no information about the possible cause of the apparent discrepancy, but suggested three possibilities: that left-handers may suffer stresses in the womb or around the time of birth that affect their longevity; that genetic effects or hormones may have hampered their immune system, or that `` left-handers may have more accidents in an environment designed for a right-handed majority.'' They concluded: `` These factors may act singly or in concert to account for the fact that left-handers seem to have a shorter lifespan.''
</TEXT>
