o early to tell if <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> will need more money. For now, he said, the bank board has $ 4 billion in cash on hand and enough additional money coming in over the next two years. `` We do n't think we can responsibly shut down thrifts at a faster pace,'' <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said. However, most of the private analysts appearing before the committee urged swift action to stem mounting losses. Because the insurance fund needs to conserve cash, it has been keeping hundreds of money-losing institutions open, hoping to persuade private investors or healthy S & amp; Ls to take them over with federal assistance. If regulators are to move faster, the key question is who should pay. <PERSON> Theo </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, the industry's largest trade group, stopped short of calling for a taxpayer bailout, but he told reporters the industry has reached the limit if what it can pay. `` We ca n't pay any more and not reduce the capital levels of this industry to perilous levels,'' he said. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> said he hoped a taxpayer rescue could be avoided, and Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, said flatly he would oppose use of tax money. However, <PERSON> Ely </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverberg </PERSON> of the Washington-based Golembe Associations and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenbaum </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said $ 30 billion to $ 40 billion in tax money would have to be spent. `` The key thing the next president has to do is recognize that the big hit must be take