<TEXT>
 Bomb experts searched the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday after a 10-day standoff between militant Sikhs and Indian security forces, and <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> gunmen reportedly killed 25 people to avenge the siege of the holy shrine. As the search for hidden explosives began, a committee of <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> elders that manages the 400-year-old temple began trying to work out ways to reopen the temple to worshipers. Police Chief K.P.S. <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said workers found four bodies inside the shrine Thursday, one day after the last of the militant Sikhs emerged and surrendered to Indian authorities. `` We are still searching for dead men and arms. It may be by the weekend we can say it is all clear,'' <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said. A curfew was in effect in the temple's immediate vicinity. Residents were kept out of an area extending for 300 yards outside the walls of the sprawling complex. The temple is the center for <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> extremists who have waged a guerrilla war since 1982 for an independent Sikh homeland in the rich farming state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Sikhs are a religious minority in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> but a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Forty-five men and one woman walked out of the temple Wednesday during a cease-fire by the 2,800 policemen, commandoes and paramilitary troops posted outside. Twelve of the men, described by authorities as `` hard-core terrorists,'' were charged with murder and possession of arms. At least 46 people, mostly militant Sikhs, died in the siege, according to official statements. Four other militants committed suicide. Despite the government's success in ending the siege, its authority is still challenged by continuing Sikh attacks elsewhere in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said Sikh gunmen shot and killed 25 people across <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> in seven separate overnight attacks, raising the death toll since the start of the year to 1,088. At least 40 people were killed Tuesday and Wednesday, including 30 migrant Hindu laborers shot to death as they slept at a camp near the state capital, <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. A note found near the laborers' bodies said the killings were to avenge the siege of the Golden Temple The temple siege _ the strongest government anti-terrorist action since a 1984 army raid on the shrine _ began May 9 after Sikh extremists inside fired at police commanders on an inspection tour outside the temple. Five officers were injured. Eight hundred pilgrims and temple workers were evacuated from the temple May 10, and 146 people, including some Sikh extremists, surrendered during a cease-fire Sunday. During the surrender Wednesday, the last of the militants emerged from the temple in small groups and were taken for questioning by police.
