<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved a $ 1.4 billion legislative branch spending bill Thursday after voting a policy of zero tolerance of drug use among its employees but refusing to extend to them any civil rights protections. The bill, passed 277-104, would increase spending by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and its agencies by 1.6 percent above current levels, including a 16.5 percent hike for its leadership staffs. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected several amendments aimed at freezing or cutting costs, accepting only a symbolic $ 5 million reduction in its estimated postage costs. For the third straight day, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved an amendment requiring that no federal funds go to a workplace where drugs are used, sold or made. The provision, offered by Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, R-Pa., was approved 286-98, despite complaints that it was an election-year gimmick that would n't solve the problem The amendment gives `` the impression that we've done something about drugs, but ... we wo n't have done a whit,'' said Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., who called it a `` garbage'' amendment Rep. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, R-Ill., was forced to withdraw her amendment requiring <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to obey the civil rights law it imposed on the rest of the nation 24 years ago The amendment banning discrimination based on race, sex, religion, age, national origin or physical handicap was deemed out of order on the spending bill. The House bill, by tradition, does not include the allowance for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where the bill was sent. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> estimated the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> portion would add $ 413 million to the total. Th