<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--Hepatitis-Drugs     05-19 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Hepatitis-Drugs,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Reports Increasing Number Of Hepatitis Cases Among Drug
Abusers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 So-called `` type A'' hepatitis, a liver disease traditionally linked to poor hygiene, is showing up more and more in outbreaks among drug abusers, federal health researchers said Thursday. Outbreaks of Hepatitis A among drug abusers have occurred in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and a variety of other locations across the country in the past two years, the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s upstate <LOCATION> Cortland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, for example, 58 percent of the hepatitis A cases last year occurred among `` known or suspected drug abusers,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. Between 1982 and 1986, the percentage of hepatitis A patients admitting previous use of injectible drugs rose from 4 percent to 19 percent, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s Viral Hepatitis Surveillance Program. Those statistics are not complete, since the program does not cover all cases, <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> researchers stressed. `` How widespread this is, we ca n't really tell,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> hepatitis specialist. `` Where there's a greater percentage of drug users, there might be a greater problem.'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> noted that health officials reporting hepatitis cases to the Atlanta-based federal agency do not routinely report patients' risk factors Hepatitis B, a blood-borne disease, has for some time been known to plague intravenous drug abusers, who can pass the disease through sharing of contaminated needles. `` But it's only newly recognized that they are a risk group for hepatitis A,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said. Hepatitis A is often transmitted in cases of poor hygiene, through fecal contamination. About 25,000 cases each of hepatitis A and B were reported to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> last year. Hepatitis is a serious inflammation of the liver, causing fever and aches, which can, in rare cases, be fatal. Two explanations have been proposed for the new link between hepatitis A and drug abuse, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. The illness may be spread through use of drugs contaminated with the virus. Or the virus might be spread in direct person-to-person contact, perhaps in needle sharing, sexual contact or poor personal hygiene. `` Investigations of the various outbreaks ... have not revealed clear modes of transmission,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in its weekly report. `` It is possible that each outbreak has multiple modes of transmission.'' In upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, in addition to the <LOCATION> Cortland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> outbreak, 87 cases of hepatitis A were reported in <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> from December 1986 to May 1987; 24 patients were injectible drug abusers, and eight more were sexual or household contacts of the drug users, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. In northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, in the wake of a food-borne hepatitis A outbreak, 33 other patients not connected to that outbreak were questioned; 24 of the 33 patients were abusers of injectible drugs. Other drug-linked outbreaks have occurred in recent years in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
