<FIRST>r a AM-KillerBees     05-19 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Killer Bees,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Killer Bees' Found On Ship Arriving In Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten thousand super-agressive `` killer bees'' almost got a free ride into <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> aboard a ship, state agriculture officials said Thursday. The killer bee colony, complete with queen bee, that was destroyed earlier this month aboard a freighter at <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> was the third and by far the largest swarm of the deadly Africanized bees that have been found on ships arriving in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> within the last two years, officials said. There was chance that the swarm could have helped establish the killer bee problem in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but the odds were against that happening because the bees would probably have bred with their gentler cousins, officials said. The nasty little bugs, descended from South African bees that escaped from a researcher in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in 1956, attack much more agressively when riled than do ordinary honeybees. They have been blamed for several deaths of humans and livestock in the areas in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> where they have taken over, and are also a threat to the commercial beekeeping industry. Some researchers fear they could spread across the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> border into <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> as early as the end of this year. About 10,000 bees were clustered aboard the containerized freighter <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, carrying fruit and vegetables from <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, when it docked May 6 near <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, said state Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>. The inspector who destroyed the swarm, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bastianelli </PERSON>, was stung more than 100 times. But it takes about 2,000 stings to kill an average adult, said <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON>, the state's chief apiary -LRB- beehive -RRB- inspector. If they had gotten ashore, <PERSON> Bastianelli </PERSON> said, the bees could have set up a hive and begun expanding because they included a queen, the only member of a colony that can reproduce. But <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON> said a single colony is not much of a threat in itself because bees do not inbreed. A single colony would breed with European honey bees and the Africanized strain would be reduced with each generation until eventually it would be bred out of existence, he said. `` There's always a chance'' of the bees becoming established, said <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON>. `` Just what that chance is, we do n't know.'' Since 1986, signs have been posted at ports urging crews and dock workers to report swarms and its now common knowledge among seaman that authorities want to know about bee activity on ships. Also, bee-nesting lures have be placed at major ports to attract bees before they can move inland, officials said. `` They'll go to a bee box before they go anywhere else, hopefully,'' <PERSON> Bustianelli </PERSON> said. `` Once we find out there are bees there we can get them, although we might have to fight them a while.'' In late 1986, a colony of killer bees was discovered and destroyed aboard a ship docked in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. Another was removed by a hobbyist beekeeper in April 1987 from a freighter in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and later destroyed by agriculture officials. The Port Everglades swarm was considerably larger than the others, <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON> said, but it was still about a fifth the size of a normal, established colony. The bees also were infested with Varroa mite, a honeybee pest detected in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> two years ago and since found in 13 other states including <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON> said. Like the killer bee, the mite is considered a potential major threat to the beekeeping industry. The mite feeds on the body fluid of bees and pupae, eventually causing high bee mortality and weakening of colonies. The discovery of mites in the <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> swarm has increased suspicion the mite infestation that began two years ago was caused by an Africanized colony which became established without detection, <PERSON> Cutts </PERSON> said.
