<TEXT>
 About 200,000 people gathered peacefully in a square in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> Thursday in the second large demonstration in the Armenian capital this week, an Armenian activist said. Several assemblies were held this week in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> to address ethnic unrest in the republics. Armenians want the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> area of neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> to become part of their republic. Activist <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> that some people in the crowd Thursday carried banners demanding annexation of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region. However, it was not clear who called Thursday's demonstration, or what its purpose was, he said. There were rumors it had been organized by officials, and people may have been attracted by curiosity, he said. But nothing happened in the two hours after people began to gather at 6 p.m. -LRB- 9 a.m. EDT -RRB- in a square near the city opera house, he said. `` People were standing around; there were n't any microphones,'' <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON> said. Police surrounded the square but did not interfere, he said. The majority of the people in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> are <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenians </ORGANIZATION>, and Armenians say they are repressed by Azeris, who are Moslems. <PERSON> Papoyan </PERSON> said there was a `` constant danger of an explosion'' of rage in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. Armenians had been forced out of the city of <LOCATION> Shusha </LOCATION> in the region by other residents, and soldiers were surounding <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, he said. Other calls to officials and activists in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> did not go through. Armenians began protesting in mid-February f