</LOCATION> on May 11 that had worried some Azeris. It did not elaborate. <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON> said there had been reports of clashes between Azeris and Armenians in the region, but that he did not have details. <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> radio said members of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Azerbaijan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet met with some of those attending the meetings and urged restraint. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryabokon </PERSON>, an editor of the dissident journal Express-Khronika, said in a telephone interview that tens of thousands of people gathered in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> on Monday and Tuesday to demand that courts not give the death sentence to any of those charged in the <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> riots.
