<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Many Statements Made To Congress Can Be Used in
Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with more details from filings.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> made damaging admissions to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> about the Iran-Contra affair that could be used as evidence against them in court, prosecutors said Thursday. <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>'s statement that he approved <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s plan to funnel profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels and admissions by him and <PERSON> North </PERSON> that they destroyed documents during a 1986 investigation were among numerous excerpts of congressional testimony that prosecutors said were admissible in court. Even though they testified on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> under limited grants of immunity from prosecution, former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> North </PERSON>, <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and arms dealer <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> made statements that can be used against them when the Iran-Contra case goes to trial in federal court, the prosecution said. `` Volunteered testimony by defendants in their congressional testimony is not immunized and may be directly introduced at trial against them,'' independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said in briefs filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The three defendants are accused along with retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, who gave congressional testimony without an immunity grant, of conspiring to defraud the government by diverting profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels. The indictment includes charges that <PERSON> North </PERSON> destroyed documents during the November 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation of the Iran-Contra affair that uncovered the diversion of arms-sale profits. It also accuses <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and North of lying to congressional committees by denying involvement in private Contra resupply efforts. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> offered to `` forego the use of congressional testimony'' to smooth the way for a quick trial as a way of satisfying defense complaints that the prosecution illegally relied on immunized statements of the defendants. However, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> cited hundreds of statements by <PERSON> North </PERSON>, <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> that were either voluntary or not responsive to the specific question posed by the committees and therefore not covered by the immunity grants. In a joint filing, defense lawyers called `` simply absurd'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s claim that the three defendants waived their privilege against self-incrimination during the congressional hearing. `` Each defendant claimed his privilege at the very outset and never relinquished it,'' the defense said. `` The court should flatly reject the IC's -LRB- independent counsel's -RRB- attempt to circumvent the immunity statute.'' The defense also urged the judge to dismiss the indictment on the ground that <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> took insufficient steps to isolate his staff from the defendants' immunized testimony, which `` has seeped into every corner of this case.'' The statements that <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> maintains are not covered by the immunity grants included <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>'s assertion that the diversion proposed by <PERSON> North </PERSON> `` was clearly a new aspect that I had not thought about before. To make a long story short, in the end I thought it was a very good idea ... and I personally approved it.'' `` In my view,'' <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> continued, `` it was a matter of implementation of the president's policy with regard to support for the Contras.'' <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> also admitted that he `` made a very deliberate decision not to ask the president so that I could insulate him from the decision and provide some future deniability for the president if it ever leaked out.'' The excerpts also include <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s statements that he shredded <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> documents while <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials were in the next room during the November 1986 inquiry, prosecutors said in the briefs. `` I remember shredding documents while they were in there reading documents,'' <PERSON> North </PERSON> told the committee. `` Do you remember _ shredding them in their presence?'' asked <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Liman </PERSON>, counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel. `` I mean, they were sitting in my office and the shredder was right outside and I walked out and shredded documents,'' <PERSON> North </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> contended he could also use <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>'s statements that he intended to withhold information from the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and his belief that <PERSON> North </PERSON> was evasive and withheld information from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` I testified that I have withheld information from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and with regard to Cabinet officers, I did n't withhold anything from them that they did n't want withheld from them,'' <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> told the panel. Of <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> testified, `` I expected him to be evasive.'' <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> said he was sure <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s answers `` were very carefully crafted, nuanced. The total impact, I'm sure, was one of withholding information from the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, meanwhile, also asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> to set a trial date, arguing that defense claims that the prosecution illegally relied on compelled congressional testimony were meritless. He argued that <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> should set a trial date and reserve judgment on the immunity issues until later. `` A demand for any further pre-trial hearings -LRB- by the defense -RRB- would constitute a transparent attempt at delay,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> argued.
