<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Conservative Republicans, spurning appeals from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders, urged colleagues on Thursday to ignore the fast approaching U.S.-Soviet summit and debate the medium-range arms reduction treaty for weeks. But Senate Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> said: `` It's our president who will be in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> next week and he'd like to have this treaty. I say that as Republican leader on behalf of a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> president. `` We have a special responsibility to President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty calls for the elimination of all ground-launched missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles. Shortly before <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> appealed to senators to bring any amendments they may have to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor for action, Sen. <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>., told his colleagues: `` We should not be playing beat the clock in our debate over the treaty. `` We can not feel rushed by the artificial deadline of next week's summit,'' <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON> said. `` It should be beside the point to meet a deadline.'' Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, said: `` Let us examine this treaty carefully and let the public relations deadline in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> be damned.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s summit meeting with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is set to open May 29. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, noting that no amendments had been offered to the text of the treaty at that point, asked unanimous consent to move to the resolution of Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, the leading opponent of the treaty, objected, saying amendments were being prepared by as many as four senators. About an hour later, Sen. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, introduced an amendment that would prevent the treaty from going into effect until the president certifies the Soviets are in compliance with all other arms control treaties. He asked for separate roll call votes on all five sections of the amendment, probably on Friday morning. `` The Soviets cheated in the past and I think we can expect they are going to cheat in the future and I think each senator ought to go on record whether he wants to condone cheating or not,'' <PERSON> Symms </PERSON> said. But Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, noted that Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> testified that the treaty `` stands on its own merits and should not be linked to other arms control treaties or other issues.'' `` It would be like cutting off our nose to spite our face,'' <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind., said that linking the INF treaty to other issues `` is not in the best interest of our country. `` The INF treaty is not a favor to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` To make implementation depend on compliance with other treaties is nonsensical.'' `` To deny ourselves a national security option does not make good sense,'' <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> said. `` This treaty stands on its own merits.'' Earlier, <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON> conceded the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> eventually will ratify the treaty, but he urged rejection of `` the drumbeat from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and our leadership which demands our swift consent to the INF treaty.'' Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, raised the possibility a filibuster may have begun and said, `` I think if we were to vote tonight it would be a surprise if there were 10 no's. I think the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> deserves an opportunity for this body _ before he meets in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> _ to say yes or no.'' Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, R-Ind., told him: `` I do n't think now is the time to start harping that we have to do this by a certain deadline. Wallop added: `` For us to be hurried to suit the climate of a summit is just a wrong urging at this moment.'' Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, R-Wash., a treaty supporter, said: `` This treaty should not be asked to bear the burden of amendments which are nothing more than thinly veiled attempts to delay its ratifications. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said hardcore arms control opponents have described the treaty unfairly. `` For some, the treaty apparently would result in apocalyptic military consequences,'' he said. `` That means we have had a steady stream of misleading, false testimony from the very military leaders we depend upon, and I do n't think that's true.'' `` We do this treaty a disservice if we treat it as something more or less than what it is, a single step back from the nuclear precipice,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` I think it is time to focus on what is in front of us instead of trying to bring in all of the non-related, non-germane elements. Although debate was sporadic, Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stennis </PERSON>, D-Miss., the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s most senior member, endorsed the pact, calling it a `` small first step in the long and difficult process'' of `` reducing the likelihood of a nuclear holocaust. But <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> denounced it, saying, `` The INF treaty is a fraud, a dangerous fraud.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 91-6 Wednesday to reject the first conservative attack on the treaty. That was a point of order raised by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, who claimed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was n't authorized to sign the pact and it was therefore invalid. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told reporters on Thursday: `` The first vote would indicate the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> did not think it was a serious point. I did not think it was.''
