<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> lost up to 15,000 soldiers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, a government official said Thursday as the first contingent of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops was arriving home from the war with Moslem guerrillas. <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosental </PERSON>, a political observer for the official Novosti press agency, told reporters that a Western estimate of 12,000 to 15,000 Soviet deaths in the army's 8 -LCB- years in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> was approximately correct. It was the first time a Soviet official gave any estimate of Soviet losses in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Soviet officials have refused to specify the death toll or even the number of Soviet troops deployed there. In other developments Thursday, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s acting foreign minister implied his country will continue to help arm the anti-communist guerrillas, and <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> complained to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitors that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was sending arms to the Afghan guerrillas. The Soviet withdrawal began Sunday, in accordance with a U.N.-mediated peace accord signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. The first 1,300 Soviets to leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> crossed the border into <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> on Wednesday. Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> reported that the returning soldiers sent a message to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> urging him `` to use <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s prestige and your personal authority on behalf of this humane goal _ that of bringing war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to an end and to ensure that no more bombs fall, no more people die and no more children become invalids.'' <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said Thursday that high-ranking <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and Foreign ministry officials would meet with reporters next week to discuss <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rosental </PERSON> was asked at a news conference how many Soviet soldiers had died in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He reviewed various Western media assessments, including a report by Agence France-Presse that 12,000 to 15,000 Soviets had been killed. `` I think the figures cited by Agence France-Presse are more or less correct, but you can obtain more correct figures from our military men,'' <PERSON> Rosental </PERSON> said. A Soviet-inspired revolution in April 1978 brought a Marxist leadership to power in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The Kremlin dispatched troops and tanks in December 1979 to help the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government fight guerrillas. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report released in December estimated the number of deaths and injuries among Soviets serving in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since 1979 to be `` at least 33,000 to 38,000,'' with at least a third of them fatalities. In addition, many soldiers died from diseases, the report said. If the death figures mentioned by <PERSON> Rosental </PERSON> are correct, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> suffered far fewer losses in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> did during the Vietnam War, when about 50,000 Americans were killed or mortally wounded. <PERSON> Rosental </PERSON> rejected a reporter's suggestion that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> was abandoning an allied government still beleaguered by a nationwide insurgency. `` To withdraw troops does not mean to leave the country in the lurch,'' he said. `` We leave many cultural and economic facilities there.'' The head of the Soviet contingent in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, told reporters in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> last week that more than $ 1 billion in bases and equipment were to be left behind for the Afghan government's use. Soviet soldiers have contended the Afghan army, estimated at 40,000 soldiers, can protect the government. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s acting foreign minister, <PERSON> Zain </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON>, returned Thursday from a visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The official Pakistani news agency, APP, quoted him as saying that although `` the purpose of the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> mission to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was of goodwill,'' his country would abide by the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord and the policy of `` symmetry.'' Under that policy, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will continue to supply the guerrillas and Afghan government forces, respectively, until one of the sides stops. `` I have been quoted as saying that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will stop all assistance to the mujahedeen -LRB- rebels -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said, according to APP. `` This is incorrect ... We will fulfill all obligations that we have taken upon -LRB- ourselves -RRB- in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord and after -LRB- the Soviet pullout -RRB- becomes operative on May 15, 1988.'' <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is bound by the accord to stop serving as conduit for military supplies to the rebels, which mainly come from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> officially denies it has ever helped ship the arms.
