<HEAD>Sentencing Guidelines Declared Unconstitutional Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, bgng: ``Public Citizen ...'' to UPDATE with
petition being filed.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Joining a growing number of jurists, a federal judge here on Thursday declared unconstitutional the sentencing guidelines implemented last fall for federal crimes. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> ruled that the 1984 law setting up a commission appointed by the president to write the guidelines violated the constitutional doctrine of separation of powers. The judge found that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had unconstitutionally delegated legislative power to the seven-member <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Sentencing Commission. `` The system thus departs from the basic principle that those who make or administer this nation's laws shall be accountable for their actions,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> ruled. He accused lawmakers of relinquishing their power `` to insulate <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from extended debate and political complaint.'' `` It also departs from the Constitution's requirement for clear delineations between and among the three branches of government,'' he said of the system. The judge, however, stayed his order pending <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review of the question. So far, 59 federal judges have struck down the guidelines as unconstitutional, while 31 have upheld the regulations. Public Citizen, a <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> group that is challenging the guidelines on behalf of criminal defendants, and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday petitioned the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to review a decision by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> that struck down the guidelines. The petition seeks high-court review before the decision is appealed to the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. The guidelines, intended to eliminate wide disparities in sentences for the same crimes, provide a complicated formula for determining prison terms for defendants convicted of federal crimes. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said he was particularly troubled by the lack of accountability for the way sentences are imposed under the guidelines, which took effect last fall for crimes committed after Nov. 1. `` No one _ criminal defendant, victim, and the public _ can know who or what branch of government is responsible for sentences that are imposed, and there is no one who can legitimately be held accountable, politically or otherwise, for sentences that may be regarded as too lenient,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> wrote. `` The simple and constitutionally tested system of allocating responsibility for crafting sentencing policy to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and for imposing individual sentences to a particular judge is essentially gone, replaced by a hodge-podge of contributions to sentencing from personnel from several different branches'' of government, he added. The commission includes three judges who are appointed by the president from a list of six federal judges submitted by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Judicial Conference. Unlike the delegation of legislative powers to regulatory agencies, `` the matters being delegated involve not the regulation of economic forces and factors but basic policy decisions of law enforcement, of criminal control and of punishment,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. The case before <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> involved a defendant convicted last month of possessing cocaine with intent to distribute. Defense attorney <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON> said that under the old sentencing rules, client <PERSON> Wilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodie </PERSON> would face a minimum imprisonment of five years. English said the guidelines would require a much longer minimum sentence but that without the probation department's report it would be impossible to predict what the regulations would prescribe.
