/LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, the Soviets admitted they had erred when they claimed AIDS to be a creation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> germ warfare research. Yet they continued sporadically to spread the AIDS disinformation story. After a Soviet-American meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> April 20-22 to discuss media relations, <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> said `` promises were made that this disinformation would now cease.'' `` Already we have seen _ perhaps _ the first fruits of our discussions on disinformation,'' <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> said. He said future Soviet actions would determine how sincere the Soviet undertakings are. In a later interview Wednesday with editors and reporters of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> cited other Soviet moves to improve U.S.-Soviet contacts. He said these included a Soviet agreement to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION>'s radio network, to cover the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit this month. He added that `` it also looks like'' <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> will be allowed to open a bureau in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` Amerika,'' <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION>'s Russian-language magazine, may be allowed to increase its circulation from 14,000 to 100,000 copies <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> said Soviet citizens will also be able to purchase American books by mail order at a permanent American book display in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that officials have lifted restrictions on the sale of <LOCATION> Ameri