<HEAD>Bush Wants to Be `Education President' But Offers Few Specifics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Everywhere he goes, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> talks about wanting to be `` the education president,'' singling it out as one area he would emphasize more than President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. But the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee-in-waiting has offered few specifics on how he would carry out that mission, apart from proposing a new tax break for college savings accounts and promising to support the Head Start program for disadvantaged children. At a recent campaign stop in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, pressed to explain how a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration would handle education differently, the vice president said he would bring outstanding school teachers to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for recognition ceremonies. He also called for restoration of `` the four R's: reading, ` riting, ` rithemetic and respect But those are precisely the kinds of bully pulpit efforts that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his secretary of education, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, have specialized in. School recognition programs are already a regular Rose Garden feature, blossoming in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years even while the president sought to slash the education budget. Former <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> identifies as one his education advisers, said in an interview, `` I think he's not yet spelled out his views in a number of areas and I'm looking forward to his doing that. The former governor, who launched a 10-point program in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> that included a controversial, ground-breaking career-ladder plan for teachers, said he expects <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will `` put education right up there with peace and prosperity as a concern of his administration. ... If he carries through with that for eight years, he will have a massive effect on how Americans value and view education.'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said the next president should look `` for ways to help communities make schools better, including helping to pay the bill.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> activists at a fund-raiser in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, last month, `` I do n't want to have the federal government come in and tell the superintendents in these schools, ` Here's your curriculum. Here are the A, B's and C's and you got to follow it.' ... But I do want to see the federal government used to put more emphasis on excellence.'' Pressed to spell out what he meant, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` I want to build on education, add to the concept of an education president. Because as I look at our ability, and some would say inability, to compete, the answer is education. ... It's not going to be a radical philosophical change; it's going to be a question of emphasis.'' `` It wo n't be turning my back on a record that I have identified with,'' he added. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> recently visited <ORGANIZATION> Garfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in the barrio of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where scores of Hispanic students have won honors in calculus under the tutelage of prize-winning teacher <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON>. A new movie, `` Stand and Deliver,'' celebrates <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON>'s success story. When one of <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON>'s pupils asked the vice president if money would be available to help them attend college, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> replied, `` I think the federal government has a responsibility _ there will be a change of priorities to some degree'' under his administration. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added, `` The problem is there is always going to be a limitation in what the federal government can do. In this country, if you can afford to pay for a kid's education, you should do it.'' In <LOCATION> Vandalia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, when a <ORGANIZATION> Butler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> student asked how <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would help public schools in financial trouble, he replied: `` The federal government should not create increased funding for the public schools. That's not the function of the federal government the way I see it,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a product of prep schools and <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, supports tuition tax credits for private-school parents, but has not made clear whether he would seek, as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did, vouchers that poor parents could spend on public or private education. He told the students in <LOCATION> Vandalia </LOCATION>, `` I like the idea of trying to get as much competition going between the schools as possible. ... I would n't want to do anything to weaken the public school system, although I think we should have the challenge and diversity that we've got in the way of private schools and parochial schools.'' Elsewhere, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said the federal government pays 7 percent of schools' bills and `` that's about right.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which tracks school finance, contends the federal share of public elementary and secondary expenditures has dropped during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration from 9.2 percent to 6.2 percent. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said, `` I love the concept of Head Start,'' the $ 1.2 billion preschool program for disadvantaged children. Although Head Start was included in the 1982 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` safety net,'' it serves only 445,000 children, or 16 percent of those eligible, according to the Children's Defense Fund. The government's biggest school aid program, the $ 4.5 billion Chapter 1 remedial program for the disadvantaged, reaches nearly 5 million children, but still only half those who need it. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> twice sought to cut the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> budget by $ 5 billion. The only increases he proposed were in election years: 1984 and 1988. In his first term, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sought deep cuts in Chapter 1 as well as aid for teaching the handicapped, bilingual education and help for college students. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, nevertheless, has boosted the education budget to more than $ 21 billion from less than $ 15 billion. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also speaks frequently about his desire to `` strengthen student aid for those that need it,'' including loans for college, <ORGANIZATION> Pell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grants </ORGANIZATION> and the college work-study program. But he will have to reconcile those intentions with another promise: his plan to seek a modified four-year freeze on the federal budget, with the exception of Social Security, that would allow spending to rise no more than 4 percent a year. Education accounts for only a tiny portion of the trillion-dollar federal budget, but most school programs fall into the category of discretionary spending where the pressure from a freeze would be greatest. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says with disdain that, `` The liberals, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, their answer is, ` Hey, if you really believe in education, double the spending' ... I'm going to be saying, ` Great. How are you going to pay for it and why is it better to have it dictated from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>?''' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>, has been a longtime activist in the fight against adult illiteracy, and he frequently tells audiences that 13 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s 17-year-olds are functionally illiterate. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> often extols public-private sector partnerships as a tool in the fight against illiteracy. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says he is also getting education advice from <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Packard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> founder who headed a federal panel that called two years ago for more federal support for university researh. After a recent tour of coal research facilities at <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Morgantown </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` The people working in research institutions around this nation ... pushing back the frontiers of human understanding will have more of an impact on the 21st century than all of us down in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>.''
</TEXT>
