<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 21st graf beginning ``Gen. John...'' to CORRECT spelling
of name from Pietrowski to Piotrowski.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> as president needed to get away for a while before he went to Camp David with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> and Egyptian President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, his thoughts turned to fly fishing. `` When I was president, <PERSON> Rosalynn </PERSON> and I fly fished out West,'' he says. On the pre-Camp <PERSON> David </PERSON> trip, `` I took along with me the briefing books that I would be using to prepare myself for the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> negotiations, so it was a combination of delightful surroundings, good companions ... and also just clearing my mind when I was ready to embark on one of the major challenges of my presidency.'' He now fly fishes throughout the world, but loves to come home to north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> to the little log cabin he furnished with his handmade wooden furniture. `` The cabin is within 20 feet of <LOCATION> Turnip </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, which has a fairly good native population of rainbow trout. It's the perfect environment for writing in placid, beautiful surroundings, in almost total isolation. When <PERSON> Rosalynn </PERSON> and I are there, which is never enough, it makes for good thoughts and productive days.'' The former president has written a new book, `` An Outdoor Journal: Reflections and Adventures,'' recalling favorite fishing experiences. Writing it, he said, was `` a labor of love.'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>: `` I bet I was the only American in World War II who parachuted into Occupied <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> with a fly rod. I used it, too.'' The son of legendary fisherman and writer <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> now lives in <LOCATION> Ketchum </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, between angling excursions to distant parts of the globe. But some of his most vivid memories are of his happy days on clear rivers with his father. `` When I was 6, before I'd ever picked up a fly rod, I spent one whole summer watching him fish the <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s Fork River of the Yellowstone,'' <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> says. `` Finally, at the very end, when I'd spent the whole summer building up the need to fish, my father taught me how to cast. Author of `` Misadventures of a Fly Fisherman,'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> says his love for the sport has lasted throughout his life. Not so for his late father. `` Dad had a big nice trunk, outfitted with all his rods and reels and tackle, everything he had collected over his years of fly fishing,'' remembers <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>. `` Right after that wonderful summer on the <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s Fork, in the fall of 1939, he had the trunk shipped by railway express, and they lost it. He never trout fished again. I think it was as if he felt he'd have to start all over again and it just was n't worth the trouble.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>: `` I took my wife fishing on our honeymoon and she has n't been since,'' says the former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> now teaches at <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and is chairman of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment banking firm. When he resigned from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> last year, he said he planned to go fishing. `` I went maybe eight times last summer, I ought to be doing more,'' says <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, who's cast for trout in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. `` You're out with nature and all that stuff. It's nice to be more or less alone, testing your wits and skill But I'm a real amateur. In the winter, he ties his own flies at his <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> home and plots a warm weather assault on distant rivers, perhaps in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. `` From now on I'm going to grab fishing whenever I can get it.'' <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgens </PERSON>: `` On the first date with my future husband my train into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was late, so he occupied his time by going to <ORGANIZATION> Abercrombie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON> and buying some artificial flies. He was very surprised when he showed them to me and I started identifying them. Our mutual enthusiasm for fly fishing was certainly a plus.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Morgens </PERSON> is a veteran member of Trout Unlimited's board of directors and chairs the nominating committee. `` Both my parents were fishermen _ my mother once held a blue marlin record _ and since I was an only child I spent a lot of time doing male sort of things with them. I grew up before the women's lib thing, so fishing taught me how to do things on my own, taught me I could go off alone without needing any help In those days there were n't that many things which could teach women to be independent, but fly fishing was one of them.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Morgens </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Ned </PERSON>, live in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Norwalk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gowdy </PERSON>, who for 20 years hosted The American Sportsman on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>: `` When we'd go fishing, my dad would say, ` <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON>, remember the buffalo There were millions of them before the white man wiped them out for money. That could happen to trout, too.' So from the very beginning, when I learned to fly fish at the age of 8, I was always a catch-and-release fisherman.'' He fishes almost everywhere now, and wherever he goes he preaches conservation. Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Piotrowski </PERSON>, commander in chief of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, puts in crowded workdays in his <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> headquarters, `` but sometimes in the evenings I can slip away, up into the mountains, and fly fish. `` I always like to match wits with a trout. It's great when you win, but the alternative is n't desirable. It's very humbling to come home empty-handed.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>, assistant secretary of the interior, is partial to fishing in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, but spends more time fishing on the East Coast. `` Before I was working and got married and had kids I went fly fishing 40 or 50 times a year,'' he says. `` Now I'm lucky if I go 15 times a year. But I dream about it a lot.'' `` I like companions who have the same appreciation for the sport's traditions and ethics as I do, and who provide just enough subtle competition on the stream to make it intriguing.''
</TEXT>
