<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction of single-family homes dipped in April, the government has reported, providing evidence that higher mortgage interest rates may be dampening building activity. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that single-family home building dropped 6.9 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.10 million units last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of crude oil rose 24.1 percent in April from year-earlier levels while total domestic production registered a 2.7 percent decline, a trade association said. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday in its Monthly Statistical Report that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of crude oil and petroleum products averaged 7.04 million 42-gallon barrels daily in April, up from 5.77 million barrels daily in April 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has refunded $ 55.9 billion to taxpayers this year, about one-eighth of the personal income taxes that were collected in advance in 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that 65.1 million couples and individuals, or 80.4 percent of the returns that have been processed so far this year, qualified for refunds. The refunds averaged $ 860. The total number of refunds was up slightly, from 64.8 million last year. The amount refunded declined, from $ 56.1 billion, as did the average, from $ 866.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief economic adviser predicts there will be a loss of more than 600,000 jobs if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> increases the minimum wage from the current $ 3.35 to $ 4.65 an hour over three years. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, chairman of the president's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, said in a letter released Wednesday to Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petri </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., that job losses `` would be concentrated among younger, less skilled and minority workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steelmakers are prepared to file a wave of unfair trade suits against foreign competitors if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> voluntary import quota plan is not extended, according to the leader of the domestic industry. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> steel industry ... will not stand idly by and watch ... import abuses which threw our companies into a five-year bath of red ink,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. Voluntary restraint agreements negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration with 31 foreign nations are due to expire in September 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
