<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rate Concerns Depress Stocks, Single-Family Housing Construction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Concerns about rising interest rates are depressing the stock market and the single-family home segment of the construction market, analysts say. On Wall Street, stock prices slumped Wednesday for the second consecutive session, sending one widely-watched market indicator to a three-month low. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 35.32 to 1,951.09, the lowest level since it closed at 1,914.46 on Feb. 9. Broader market measures also tumbled. Bond prices fell broadly, pushing interest rates higher. The yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond, regarded as an indicator of interest rate speculation, rose to 9.29 percent from 9.21 percent late Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said single-family home building dropped 6.9 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.10 million units last month. Construction of multi-family units, which swing widely from month to month, soared by 23.3 percent to a rate of 466,000 units. Overall, housing construction rose 0.5 percent in April to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 1.56 million units, following gains of 2.3 percent in March and 9.9 percent in February, the report stated. But housing activity was still 4.5 percent below last year. Economists said the increase in apartment building probably was an aberration and rising mortgage interest rates likely would depress single-family construction. `` The single-family number is not a bad number, but I think it's an indication that as rates rise through the year, it's going to impact the housing market,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> A Regalia, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>. Rates on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages were just under 10 percent through March, but began edging up in April and averaged 10.4 percent last week. Housing permits, considered a good sign of future construction activity, fell 4.1 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.42 million units. Single-family permits fell 6.8 percent, while multi-family units rose 2.2 percent. In other economic news Wednesday: _ President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief economic adviser, <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, said there will be a loss of more than 600,000 jobs if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> increases the minimum wage from the current $ 3.35 to $ 4.65 an hour over three years <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> said in a letter to Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petri </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., that the job losses `` would be concentrated among younger, less skilled and minority workers. _ <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> imports of crude oil rose 24.1 percent in April from year-earlier levels while total domestic production declined 2.7 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported. The trade group said that unlike previous months, the latest domestic production figure did not include a year-to-year increase in Alaskan output to partially offset a decline in the lower 48 states.
