<SECOND>PM-Steel,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Steelmakers Demand Negotiation, Threaten Litigation Over
Import Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Failure to renew <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel import quotas may trigger a wave of trade litigation by American companies against foreign competitors, including <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the head of the main domestic industry trade group says. Meanwhile, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steelmakers said Wednesday the recovery that trade protection helped made possible in their industry may have peaked for the time being. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> steel industry, so hard at work to make itself internationally competitive, will not stand idly by and watch that work undone by a repeat of the import abuses which threw our companies into a five-year bath of red ink,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, whose election to a rare third term as <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> chairman was announced Wednesday. Voluntary restraint agreements negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> adminisration with 31 foreign steelmaking nations expire in September 1989. The five-year quota plan was instituted partly to end a barrage of steelmaker lawsuits, many of them aimed at the government-subsidized mills of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` If a VRA extension is deemed unecessary by those in government, then we're prepared to flood the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- with trade case filings, if need be, in numbers which will make what came before the VRAs seem trivial by comparison,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said in a speech at the <ORGANIZATION> AISI </ORGANIZATION>'s annual conference. `` We do not want protection from efficient competition, nor do we need it,'' he said. `` We need and expect only a climate of fair trade and legal trading practices.'' Earlier Wednesday in a panel discussion, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' largest trading partner and the largest steel exporter not covered by the voluntary quotas, is vulnerable to a trade suit. The AISI, to which Canadian mills belong, wants <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> included if the quotas are extended. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> boosted its share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel market from what <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said is its fair share of 2.4 percent to 3.7 percent in 1987. The increase disadvantages <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other quota nations, he said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON>, chairman of the Canadian steelmaker <ORGANIZATION> Stelco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said in a speech Monday in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel exports have surged from 4.5 percent and 4.8 percent of the Canadian market in 1985 and 1986 respectively to 5.5 percent last year. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> also said Canadian steel is fairly traded. Separately, other industry leaders said steel's recovery may have peaked if, as they fear, customers soon stop building inventories. `` We're forecasting a decrease in the production rates in the automobile, appliance and private housing sectors. So we do n't see any driving forces for a continuation of the demand we're seeing today,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boni </PERSON> <PERSON> Boni </PERSON> said 1988 shipments probably would tail off to 75.5 million tons, roughly even with the 76 million tons shipped in 1987 and considerably shy of the 80 million tons talked about earlier this year, the second year of the industry's long-awaited recovery. The shipping rate bears directly on profits and employment. `` The reduction of 5 million tons obviously ... is going to reduce profits,'' <PERSON> Boni </PERSON> said without offering specific figures. But officials said they doubted such a slowdown sales would force any plants to close. `` The most difficult thing for us to call in this equation is customer inventory'' because no accurate surveys are available, said <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoag </PERSON> `` We know the customers built a lot of inventory last year. We feel certain they built some in the first half of this year and at some point they will discontinue building those inventories,'' he said. `` I think that will begin to occur sometime in the second half.''
