<HEAD>Oilfield Equipment Maker Wants Your Spare Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the going got tough, one oil patch company turned to the newspaper classifieds for help. `` Please send MONEY. <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> needs cash to keep 50 people in jobs,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> ad placed by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Fitting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I had hoped I would never have to -LRB- place such an ad -RRB-,'' company president <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` I'm not good at begging, but I think it has come to be just that.'' The ad, which appeared Tuesday, said contributors would not receive stock or securities, but merely a thank you from the company. The ad included a post office box where contributions could be sent. By early Wednesday afternoon, about 150 people had called the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> company since the ad appeared, most asking for the company's address, <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said. `` They just indicated they would be putting something in the mail,'' <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said. Federal Flange, which produces pipe flanges used in oil fields, suffered severely in the energy downturn. The company slashed its workforce from 160 employees to about 50, including three of <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>'s 12 children and two of his nephews, he said Annual revenue has plunged to about $ 3.5 million from about $ 15 million in the early 1980s. <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said the small ad also will appear in the Chronicle's sports section Sunday He said the newspaper had delayed printing it by a few days to make sure there was nothing wrong in printing it. <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said he has been thinking about placing such an ad for months, but finally decided to do so after hearing about a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> radio announcer who asked for money and got it. KVIL-FM announcer <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> asked listeners to send in $ 20 without telling them why, and the station received $ 243,120 in four days. It later gave the money to charity. But <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flange </ORGANIZATION>'s need for money was no joke. He needs it to pay overdue bills and help keep him from having to file for bankruptcy. `` I find people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are very, very generous,'' he said. `` I have a lot of confidence in the generosity of people.'' <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, who has been battling <PERSON> Hodgkin </PERSON>'s disease for two years, said he also prays for his company's survival _ not money _ during mass. `` I do n't believe in praying for money,'' he said.
