<HEAD>London Share Prices Recover From Lows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices recovered by midday Thursday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> after opening broadly lower in a response to earlier declines in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Wednesday. Traders said the market was steadying after its early jitters, helped in part by neutral British economic news reported late in the morning. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 14.8 points, or 0.8 percent, at 1,762.8 at about 12:15 p.m. local time. The index had been down as much as 24.3 points earlier in the session. Volume was 280.0 million shares, up from 255.3 million shares at midday Wednesday. Earlier in the session, the market withstood a barrage of economic reports which traders said appeared to paint a neutral picture of the <LOCATION> U.K. </LOCATION> economy. A provisional 0.9 percent rise in the money supply was considered equal to or better than market expectations. Industrial production and earnings data also suggested the economy was n't overheating Unemployment, which dropped to 8.8 percent in April from 9 percent in March, was lower than expected. `` People are n't really worried about inflation'' as they were earlier in the week following the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> March trade figures, said a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trader. `` What we're waiting for is Wall Street.'' Another weak start to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market could unnerve <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> traders. Several said the Dow Jones industrial average's drop of more than 35 points on Wednesday left Wall Street vulnerable.
