<HEAD>Amfac Management Proposes Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amfac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> management, led by the president of the San Francisco-based conglomorate, has proposed an all-cash buyout for the purchase of the company at a value of $ 41 per share. `` The company stated that it has been advised that management has been discussing financing for the buyout with a leading financial institution and is confident that such financing can be obtained,'' the company said in a statement issued on Wednesday at a special board of directors' meeting. However, the statement added that `` there is as yet no firm commitment.'' The buyout would be led by <ORGANIZATION> Amfac </ORGANIZATION> President and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>, 57. The proposed buyout is `` strongly supported by operating management,'' said <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>. He said it `` strengthens our ability to develop <ORGANIZATION> Amfac </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> asset base in a paced and profitable manner in concert with the state's economic needs and long-term growth goals.'' The plan is `` subject to obtaining the financing as well as a number of other conditions,'' including approval of the board, the company statement said. Meantime, the board decided not to proceed with the sale of the <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Resort </PERSON> operations and a 50 percent joint venture interest in its <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> land and agricultural operations. The company had received an offer of $ 166 million for <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Amfac </ORGANIZATION> is a diversified services company with main lines of business in food processing, hotels and resorts, retail, agriculture and property. Revenues in 1987 were $ 2.2 billion.
