<HEAD>Beef Prices Increase In Latest Survey, NCA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The average price of beef rose 12 cents a pound over a month ago, the Denver-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cattlemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The average price in its May 12 survey of prices in 19 cities nationwide was $ 2.82 per pound, up from $ 2.70 in the survey on April 14. Seasonal increases in demand _ especially for steak _ helped trigger the higher costs for consumer beef, the association said. Sirloin, for example, was $ 3.62 per pound, up from $ 3.30 a month ago, while round steak was up from $ 2.47 to $ 2.52. T-Bone steak averages rose from $ 4.62 to $ 4.89. Ground beef prices also rose from $ 1.40 in April to $ 1.42 in May, while chuck roast, the only category to come in lower in May, dropped from $ 1.74 to $ 1.68. The <ORGANIZATION> NCA </ORGANIZATION> said demand for roasts generally drops during summer months. The five-cut average, which also was above the average of $ 2.71 of May 1987, rose in 14 cities and was down in five. The five-cut average ranged from a low of $ 2.42 in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> to a high of $ 3.41 in both <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
