<SECOND>BC-China Eurobonds,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moody's Rates China Eurobonds Single-A-3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has assigned a single-A-3 rating to 300 million West German marks of Eurobonds issued by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and due in 1992, <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Japanese subsidiary said. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> K.K. said in a statement Wednesday that it was the first time a bond issued by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had been rated by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> credit-rating agency. The single-A-3 rating indicates that the Eurobond issue is a safe investment. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s rates bonds in 27 categories from single-C-3, the highest investment risk, to triple-A-1, the lowest risk. The <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s statement said the rating was `` based on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s current low level of debt, the expectation that future borrowing will remain within a comfortable range relative to the nation's debt-servicing capacity, and the progress made in stabilizing Chinese politics since the death of Chairman <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Zedong </PERSON> in 1976 <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign debt is low by international standards, totaling an estimated $ 27 billion at the end of last year. That represents 9.3 percent of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s gross national product and 75 percent of its current foreign-exchange receipts, the statement said. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has adopted a conservative policy toward reliance on foreign debt and ... this policy is likely to continue,'' the statement said. However, it said, `` the scope and the nature of the changes underway are unprecedented, with major policy contradictions yet to be resolved.'' `` Discontent has emerged, primarily because of the dramatic shifts in the control of resources and in the distribution of benefits, but also because progress on political liberalization has been slow,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
