<HEAD>Japan to End Voluntary Auto Export Limits to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plans to end its voluntary limit of automobile exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> effective next April, according to a news report disputed by the government. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that the government plans to end the limits. However, officials of the automobile department of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Thursday night they had not discussed the matter yet. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified <ORGANIZATION> MITI </ORGANIZATION> sources as saying ministry officials believe there is no possibility that automobile exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will become an issue again because the high value of the yen makes Japanese exports more expensive. Also, Japanese car makers now have production plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Major Japanese producers, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, also are concentrating now on exporting deluxe cars to the Untied States that compete with South Korean exports, it said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> began limiting its auto exports to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market in fiscal 1981 under strong pressure from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and the slumping American auto industry. The limit first was set at 1.68 million vehicles, but was raised to 1.86 million in fiscal 1984. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stopped asking for the restraints in 1985, but <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> voluntarily continued limiting car shipments to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market to the 2.3 million vehicles exported there in fiscal 1985. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> auto exports in fiscal 1987 were 2.21 million _ below the limit.
</TEXT>
