<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal official who headed the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s latest study of the financial market crash defended its recommendations today, saying the recent dramatic price swings on the markets do not require dramatic fixes. But members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee said they were dissatisfied with the study. `` The issue of daily volatility, although an expressed public concern, is not in the category of systemic threat, in my opinion,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>. `` However disconcerting such volatility can be on a short term basis, it is important not to attempt cures that can do more harm than good.'' Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., the subcommittee's chairman, criticized <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s report, saying, `` history will judge your work product far more harshly than -LRB- did -RRB- your boss, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The White House has praised the stock market study that <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> and his associates produced. Rep. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinaldo </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the subcommittee, said of the report's conclusions, `` They certainly did not go far enough.'' The working group that produced the study consisted of <LOCATION> Gould </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>. Their report recommended that the nation's stock, futures and options markets set up a `` circuit breaker'' that would allow them to halt all trading on days when the Dow Jones Industrial Average plunges by historic levels. The study suggested that improvements be made in the credit, clearing and settlement systems the markets use to conduct and complete transactions. In addition, the group said it should remain in existence `` to function as a coordinating and consulting mechanism for intermarket issues.'' The report offered no proposals for limiting computer-driven program trading, a strategy that involves futures and stock transactions that critics say has helped fueled the markets' volatility in recent months Also absent were recommendations to change the levels of margins, or downpayments, for futures transactions, a move that supporters say would diminish speculation. In addition, the group did not endorse a proposal advanced by an earlier <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel, headed by investment banker <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, that a single federal agency _ probably the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> _ should oversee issues that concern all of the markets. Instead, the officials seemed to shrug off the contentions of many lawmakers and investors that dramatic steps need to be taken quickly to avoid repeats of days like last Oct. 19, when the Dow plunged a record 508 points. Since that time, many small investors have left the market. `` When you get a shock to the system that occurred on Oct. 19, people withdraw,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said Monday. `` It's a cycle. They come back, they leave, they come back. ... They will be back.'' The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell more than 35 points Wednesday and was at its lowest level in more than three months.
</TEXT>
