<FIRST>a f BC-ProxyFights Adv23   05-19 1103</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Proxy Fights, Adv 23,1135</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Proxy Fights _ The Latest In Takeover Strategies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corporate takeover artists are waging their own political campaigns this election year. They call them proxy contests. Rather than merely throwing money at shareholders to buy their way into companies, raiders are exerting new pressure on their targets by trying to infiltrate the boardroom. Convinced they can do more with a company's assets than incumbent management, outsiders are asking shareholders to cast their lots with them by voting in a new regime. Often without track records of their own, raiders promise shareholders handsome returns in exchange for their support of a rival slate of board candidates. The process is not for the faint of heart or purse. Experts estimate it can cost up to $ 10 million to wage a full-blown proxy battle, replete with newspaper ads, mass mailings and phone solicitations. While that's a steep price tag for a fight that usually favors management, it's sometimes worth the expense. By testing the hinges on the palace gates, some proxy warriors have stirred entrenched managers to make big changes and raise the value of their stock to the delight of common shareholders. Corporate gunslingers have had few dead shots with the proxy weapon, but their aim is getting better. In recent weeks, managements at <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> came perilously close to losing control of their boards in heated proxy contests. Even more revealing, a study of 60 proxy fights between 1978 and 1985 conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> found that, in many cases, top managers eventually resigned even after beating back challenges from outside. A challenger's typical tactics include painting a `` broad-brush picture of managerial inefficiency, using a variety of easy-to-convey criticisms such as poor operating profits or an allegedly inadequate dividend payout,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> who co-authored the study. Until recently, proxy contests were not waged against corporate heavyweights. Experts say the new wave is a result of corporate defensive maneuvers like poison pills and state laws that make unwanted takeovers cumbersome. Poison pills and new legislation `` have become significant deterrents to the purchasing of a major stake in a company,'' <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON> said. Aggressors believe their allies, if elected, can work to rescind poison pills that may be in place and can help push for a deal. The proxy battles that ensue are `` a form of pressure on companies ... an amplification of takeover strategy,'' said attorney <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s committee on proxy fights and tender offers He noted that until recently, raiders used proxy battles `` as a way to obtain control of a whole company without paying for it ... but now we're finding a lot of these contests are connected with tender offers.'' <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> sought seats for himself and two allies on the board of <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in conjunction with his $ 1.8 billion tender offer for the communications company. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s bid was complicated by two classes of stock, one of which put control of the company in the hands of the <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family, owners of 70 percent of Media General's more powerful Class B shares. Management's main advantage in these fights is financial. Because they control the pursestrings, corporate chieftains can spend a lot of money to make their own case. `` They have all the corporte resources at their disposal _ and that's shareholder money _ to do as many mailings as they want, which is tremendously expensive,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Heard </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shareholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a shareholder rights organization headed by <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Management also has a better idea who the major shareholders are and can court them quickly Some experts estimate as much as 50 percent of a corporation's stock is held in street name, or the name of a broker or another nominee instead of the customer who will vote the shares Proxy solicitors hired by outsiders spend countless hours trying to trace shareholders through a confusing web of surface organizations. Institutional shareholders, who control a major portion of corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, often are more inclined to side with management because of possible reprisals. `` They know if they do n't, they will be punished,'' <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON> said. In <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s case, for example, institutional investors were believed to hold as much as 65 percent of the 115 million oustanding shares. One source involved in a recent, high-profile proxy battle noted that `` management has a lot more political strings to pull than the people from outside who have to persuade stockholders.'' Difficult to document but nonetheless pervasive are management threats and behind-the-scenes arm-twisting. One source said management puts pressure on institutions with which it has business relationships, sometimes threatening to sever those ties if dissatisfied with their vote. `` That's a tremendous advantage and it's very unfair,'' the source said. Winning or losing is not so easy to judge in these affairs, however. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, chief financial officer of <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, notes that it all depends on how success is measured. <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, which has had an outstanding tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, had sought six seats on the company's board. Although the results of the vote wo n't be available for some time, <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> made its point even if <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s directors are re-elected. `` Anytime a board is facing an election contest, management becomes increasingly concerned about how shareholders view the job they are doing,'' he said. `` In the case of USG, I question whether management would have ever proposed the recapitalization plan that they did ... were it not for the battle for our slate of candidates.'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> was referring to <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to spend about $ 2.2 billion to pay shareholders a one-time dividend that includes cash, stock and notes for each common share. Despite the expense and emotional wear-and-tear of a proxy battle, some say raiders merely are hoping to cash out at a higher price. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> bristled at that suggestion, noting that `` our objective is to acquire the company.'' `` You do see success in terms of what I think is a increased accountability to stockholders on the part of incumbent management and the board,'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said. Despite the advantage management might have, <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said the proxy process is a good one. `` I would hate to see any barriers to free elections of directors. I think the free-election process has tremendous motivation for incumbent management and boards to be responsive to the wishes of their constituents.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
