<FIRST>a f BC-Proxy-Management Adv23   05-19 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Proxy-Management, Adv 23,0346</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Management Suffers Even If It Wins In Proxy Contests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Proxy Fights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Winning a proxy contest is no job guarantee for current managers. According to an analysis of 60 proxy contests, management resignations typically follow a proxy battle even when outsiders fail to win seats on a company's board of directors, according to two researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION>. Professors <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON>, who studied the contests between 1978 and 1985, noted that about two-thirds of the time, top managers resigned within three years of a proxy fight, with the majority of the changes coming within one year. That includes managers who lost their jobs when disssident shareholders won control of their companies, which happened about 30 percent of the time. Perhaps even more significant, the two found that only about 20 percent of the companies they studied remained publicly held corporations run by the same management teams three years after the proxy contests. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON> pointed to two examples: _ <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Pullman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, resigned in November 1978 even though dissident shareholders were defeated in a proxy fight Two years later, the company was acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Wheelabrator-Frye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ In the case of <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION>, a group of dissident shareholders backed by <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> won four out of 10 board seats in an April 1984 proxy fight Four months later, the company's president and chief executive officer <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurshan </PERSON> resigned Within a year, the company was liquidated. The DeAngelos say their findings raise serious questions about claims that proxy contests are an inefficient way to discipline managers of publicly held corporations. In many cases of management resignations, the new manager is designed to accommodate the dissidents' interest, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON> said. `` These findings suggest that, independent of its immediate outcome, a proxy challenge does pose a serious threat to managerial tenure,'' the study said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
