<HEAD>Proxy Solicitors Thrive in New Environment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Proxy Fights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The more proxy contests, and the grizzlier, the more business booms for proxy solicitors. Solicitors are responsible for the gritty legwork in a proxy battle. They track down shareholders and talk to them, draft letters and write newspaper ads, send out mailings, tally votes, and serve as general hand-holders to whichever side they happen to represent. `` They've got it down to a science,'' one observer remarked. The <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, one of the largest solicitors with 1987 fee income of more than $ 22 million, has had a hand in several major proxy fights recently. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, the group's president, said the cost of a proxy battle can range anywhere from $ 1 million to $ 10 million. Because a large precentage of any company's stock is held by institutional investors or in street names _ names other than the actual shareholder _ simply identifying just who owns the outstanding shares is a job for a first-rate sleuth. At <ORGANIZATION> Georgeson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's oldest proxy solicitor, managing director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON> said he relies on a database that has been built up over time linking individuals and their securities holdings. Once shareholders are identified, solicitors have to convince them to vote in a particular direction. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> estimates his people talk by phone with 2 million shareholders a year in an attempt to influence voting. Some firms have even been known to hire actors to use Southern accents in an attempt to sway shareholders in Southern states, observers say. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said new technology allowing shareholders to vote by phone has `` added a new dimension'' to solicitation. `` When we get finished speaking with a shareholder, we give them a toll-free number and ask them to call immediately if they agree with us,'' he said. `` Within five minutes, we know if they're telling the truth that they're going to vote with us.'' If the shareholder does n't call in with a vote, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s people are back on the phone. Newspaper ads are also crucial to the proxy process, but they are not directed toward the individual shareholder. Rather, they are aimed at the investment community _ both large institutional investors as well as brokers who may be asked for advice from individual clients. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, chief financial officer of <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, said solicitors are `` totally key to the entire process. They help identify and contact shareholders, they give you their prognosis of how the vote is stacking up and they make sure proxies are properly executed so they do n't get thrown out on a technicality.'' Desert Partners sought seats on the board of <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in a recent proxy contest. The partnership also launched a tender offer for USG shares. As for the latest wave of proxy battles that has come to center on large corporations, `` business is the busiest ever'' for solicitors, <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
