<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> fell Thursday as the market was pressured by a slump on Wall Street. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down 17 points, or 1 percent, at 1,760.6. Volume was a moderate 438.1 million shares, compared with Wednesday's 536.1 million shares. The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as much as 25 points in the last hour of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading, disappointing many <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> players. Several dealers said rumors of large stock sales in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by Japanese investors also did not bode well for the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market. A large computer-generated trading program involving disposal of several stocks late in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> afternoon also contributed to the pressure, some traders said. `` I would say it's more a case of lethargy than outright pessimism,'' said one equity salesman, adding that `` unless we get some more bids and corporate activity, we wo n't have anything to keep the market alive.'' A battery of <LOCATION> U.K. </LOCATION> economic indicators released earlier Thursday were digested by the market without causing much of a stir, dealers said. A provisional rise in the money supply of 0.9 percent in April was equal to or better than market expectations. March industrial production rose 1.2 percent and the annual rate of increase in average earnings remained unchanged at 8.5 percent in March, suggesting the British economy was not immediately overheating. Unemployment, which dropped to 8.8 percent in April from 9 percent in March, was lower than expected.
