<HEAD>Dollar Trades in Narrow Range, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar traded in a narrow range Thursday in quiet European trading amid uncertainty about currency's direction Gold prices rose. Foreign exchange dealers said dollar trading was dull because of a lack of conviction among market players on where the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency is headed in the short-term. Dealers were also uncertain whether this week's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures, which revealed the trade deficit fell to $ 9.75 billion in March from $ 13.8 billion in February, were an aberration or the beginning of a trend. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound finished mixed. It was quoted at $ 1.8665 late Thursday, more expensive for buyers than $ 1.8605 late Wednesday. Other late dollar rates, compared with late Wednesday's prices, included: 1.6990 West German marks, down from 1.7055; 1.4155 Swiss francs, down from 1.4215; 5.7542 French francs, down from 5.7700; 1.9042 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9090; 1,262.00 Italian lire, down from 1,265.50; and 1.2442 Canadian dollars, up from 1.24125. Earlier, the dollar fell 0.73 yen to a closing 124.80 yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, in what traders said was a correction following sharp gains on the back of the trade report. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 124.87 yen. Gold prices rose in active European trading. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the metal was quoted at a late bid price of $ 456.90 a troy ounce, up from $ 453.70 late Wednesday. Dealers said a rush to buy soybeans by commodity dealers in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> helped boost gold prices. Higher prices for the beans following dry weather in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plains threaten to cause an increase in food prices and inflation and thus make gold _ a favorite hedge against inflation _ more desirable. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price for gold was $ 458, up from $ 454 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 3.02 to close at a bid $ 457.56. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 6.72 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's $ 6.58.
