<SECOND>AM-World Economy, Bjt,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Europe Set Aside Differences On Farm Trade Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A conference of leading industrial nations ended Thursday after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> failed to persuade <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> governments to accept its proposal for ending public aid to farmers by the year 2000. However, trade and finance ministers from the 24 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said they would work together to reform global farm trading rules. The European countries held out against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to set a timetable for phasing out subsidies designed to prop up farm prices and boost exports. These efforts already are under way, with little apparent progress, in the 96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a Geneva-based body that sets and monitors world trade rules. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they would have preferred a more specific commitment to press ahead with farm policy reforms, but that differences with the Europeans were not insurmountable. `` We're basically on the same wave length,'' said <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> special trade representative. `` What we achieved in this meeting is a recognition of the fact that ... we've got to begin to develop the specifics of the negotiating outlines,'' he added. Officials from other countries took a more modest view of the meeting's outcome. <PERSON> Kjell-Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldt </PERSON>, Swedish finance minister and chairman of the meeting, told reporters the Americans wanted a commitment to start reforming farm trade rules in 1989, while `` others believed it should be a gradual process.'' `` I would n't dare to say this has been resolved,'' he said. <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON>, the top trade official of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, or Common Market, would never accept the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> idea of eliminating all farm subsidies. `` For us it is a question of reduction -LRB- of subsidies -RRB-, not phasing out,'' he said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> both spend about $ 25 billion a year on farm subsidies. They agree that this aid has become too burdensome, but they disagree over how to correct the problem. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, the Austrialian foreign minister, told reporters he was pleased the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> meeting had avoided an open clash over what he called apparently irreconcilable differences between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European officials. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> made a similar assessment. `` The main thing was to avoid a needless ... clash which would have been a counterproductive signal,'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Clercq </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> communique said the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> should achieve solid progress in all areas _ including rules for trading in services such as banking _ by December, when a review conference will be held. `` As they enter their more difficult phase, it is vital to ensure the momentum of these ambitious negotiations,'' the joint declaration said. The trade and finance ministers, in a broad review of the state of the world economy, said economic growth was much stronger than had been expected in the immediate aftermath of last October's stock market crash They said world trade was growing robustly, inflation was holding at a low level, global trade imbalances were improving and international cooperation on economic issues was growing. The ministers added, however, that problems remain, including protectionism, or actions by governments to protect domestic industries from foreign competition. The statement said the top priority for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should be to further reduce its federal budget deficit. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was praised for its efforts to increase imports and stimulate domestic consumer demand. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was urged to increase the flexibility of its labor and financial markets and to reform its agricultural policies. The ministers also agreed the current approach to easing the debt burdens of poorer nations should be continued. They said each debtor's situation should be considered individually rather than applying an across-the-board formula for financial relief.
</TEXT>
