<HEAD>Directors Urged To Reject Proposal to Divide Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> executives will urge the board of directors to reject a proposal that would split the company, giving <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> industrialist <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> more than one-fourth interest in the firm's broadcast operations, according to a published report Thursday. Lawyer <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Haverford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> proposed the restructuring in a May 5 letter. <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON> represents <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, who claim in a federal court lawsuit that <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> officers and directors breached their fiduciary duty to stockholders by rejecting <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s $ 61.50-per-share offer to buy all of the company's stock. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> has since increased the offer to $ 70 per share, or about $ 2 billion. He also is waging a proxy fight to have himself and two associates elected to <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors at Friday's annual meeting. The takeover proposal will not be voted on at the meeting. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Richmond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Leader </ORGANIZATION> `` management intends to recommend against pursuing'' <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON>' proposal. `` We are not recommending any form of recapitalization at this time,'' he added. <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON> said in his letter his proposal would be better than a clear victory by either side in court. He said a <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> defeat would result in a decline in Media General stock. A <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> victory would benefit shareholders, <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON> said, `` but perhaps not the the degree available'' under his plan. The lawyer said he retained a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> investment banking company, <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, to formulate a plan that would boost stockholder value in Media General, divide the company into two units, give <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> `` a fair return on his investment'' and enable members of the <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family to retain control of the company's newsprint and newspaper businesses, which include the News-Leader and the <ORGANIZATION> Richmond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> and his associates own 10.1 percent of Media General Class A stock, an investment of more than $ 111 million. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family members own 70 percent of the company's Class B stock which, in effect, controls the company, and about 12 percent of the publicly traded Class A stock. <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON> said Media General's cable franchises in <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Fredericksburg </LOCATION>, three commercial television stations in the Southeast and a broadcast services operation are valued at about $ 580.5 million. Under the plan, <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> would be given 27 percent of the new company, based on his Media General investment. Each Media General stockholder would receive one share in the new company for each <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> share held. Under that structure, the broadcast company would be capitalized with more than 34.9 million shares of common stock, valued at about $ 16.50 each. <PERSON> Chimicles </PERSON> said the new company would be operated under a one-share, one-vote principle. The company less its broadcast properties would be operated as Media General is now, with Class B stock closely held and controlling the firm, and Class A stock publicly traded but with less voting power.
