<HEAD>Tandy Phasing Out Model 200 Laptop Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is phasing out its Radio Shack Model 200 laptop computer, a mainstay for journalists, and expects to run out of inventories by around the end of the year, the company said Thursday. The Model 200, which has a flip-up, flat-panel screen, has been reduced to a clearance price of $ 499, down from $ 799. That makes it the same price as the Model 102, which has a smaller, built-in screen and will remain in production. The Model 200 enjoyed its greatest market penetration in the newspaper business, where reporters used it to write stories while away from the office, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Juge </PERSON>, director of market planning for <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, Texas-based <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Juge </PERSON> said the Model 200 was squeezed from the bottom by the Model 102 and from the top by the Model 1400, a $ 1,499 computer introduced last August that has more memory and runs industry-standard MS-DOS software.
