<HEAD>California Company to Manufacture Guns in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gun manufacturer will make semiautomatic carbines similar to the Israeli <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> under a contract described as the first such agreement with a communist country, the company announced Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Weaver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> will sell the first shipments of its 9mm Nighthawk carbines in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and plans to sell the guns to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> police agencies, private citizens and Third World military, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, company president. The initial production agreement, which the company said was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, prohibits sale of the guns to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but the company hopes eventually to open that market, <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s public affairs office did not immediately respond to a request for confirmation that it was the first time an American gun company had been allowed to make weapons in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. One arms industry analyst downplayed the value of such a weapon to the military or police, saying there are plenty of other semiautomatic weapons available to them. Semiautomatics fire once each time the trigger is pulled. It is legal for civilians to own semiautomatic weapons in this country, but fully automatic guns are illegal. The principal value of the deal would be to give <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> a cheap product for sale to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> collectors and others who value guns that look like the short-barreled Uzis they see on television, said the analyst, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Fetter </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Forecast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Newtown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, publisher of World Weapons Week. `` Everybody wants to walk around being macho these days,'' <PERSON> Fetter </PERSON> said. `` The gun-loving public wants something that makes them look like a special forces trooper yet is legal.'' <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> signed an agreement with the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government at a ceremony May 14 in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, and expects to begin production in 90 days, with the first shipment of 10,000 guns planned by January 1989. `` We're very excited,'' <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said. `` It's an agreement that's never been accomplished before between a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> arms company and a communist country. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> refused to divulge the value of the contract or the location of the factory in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, saying the Chinese insisted on secrecy for the time being. The guns are expected to sell for $ 525 retail. The Uzi goes for $ 698 in this country, and the other similar gun, the German HK94, retails for $ 800, <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said. The publicly held company also has designed a 9mm pistol and an ultralight submachine gun, but neither is yet in production, <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said.
