<HEAD>Survey: Non-Residential Electricity Rates Fell In Year Ended April
30</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial and industrial electric users enjoyed fractionally cheaper rates in the year ended April 30, their foreign counterparts were mostly paying more, a consulting firm said Thursday. In its annual study, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said the nation's 24 largest investor-owned utilities charged their non-residential customers an average 6.28 cents per kilowatt-hour over the 12-month period, compared with 6.29 cents a year earlier. That slight decrease compared with an overall inflation rate of 3.9 percent over the same period, the firm said. `` Price reductions by some utilities could be attributed to the recent decline in oil prices,'' said <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauterbach </PERSON>, executive vice president of the Park Ridge, N.J.-based firm. But <PERSON> Lauterbach </PERSON> warned that the apparent stability masked an upward price movement by half of the utilities surveyed. `` Some of these increases are a direct result of having industrial and commercial users offset the costs incurred in the building of nuclear power plants,'' he said. `` Most of these nuclear power plants still lack a license to operate.'' Looking to other countries, the firm found that electricity costs also fell in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, by 4.87 percent, and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, by 1.98 percent. That compared with inflation rates of 2.5 percent and 0.96 percent, respectively. In <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the average cost remained constant, while inflation rose by 2.4 percent, the organization said. Countries where businesses paid more for electricity, with percentages of increases and national inflation rates were: _ <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 8.7 percent, 4.1 percent _ <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, 5.9 percent, 6.8 percent _ <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, 5.5 percent, 3.5 percent _ <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, 4.6 percent, 5.4 percent _ <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, 3.17 percent, 4.9 percent _ <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, 1.1 percent, 0.5 percent _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 0.2 percent, 0.8 percent <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is an international utility cost-consulting firm with offices in 12 nations.
