<HEAD>Bear Stearns Re-evaluating Index Arbitrage Position</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, one of several major Wall Street investment firms to cut back on program trading, said Thursday it will reconsider the move after a government official said such restrictions could destabilize the market. Bear <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> went further than four other investment firms when it announced last week it would not only stop index arbitrage trading for its own accounts but for those of customers as well. <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> halted index arbitrage for their own accounts amid concern that the popular form of program trading was at least partly responsible for the stock market's volatility. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said Thursday that excessive restriction of index arbitrage would limit market liquidity and tend to destabilize the market. In testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that `` insufficient arbitrage between cash and futures can be a destabilizing force in a declining market.'' In index arbitrage, traders use computers to buy or sell baskets of stocks with offsetting trades in stock-index futures to help them profit from brief price discrepancies. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> noted that `` reduced arbitrage implies less connection between cash and futures markets and more price disparities across these markets.'' Partly citing those comments, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bear </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON>' chairman and chief executive officer, said the firm would `` re-examine its position on index arbitrage. <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bear </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> had been `` monitoring closely the action and the liquidity problems of the stock market for the past week.'' He also pointed to other firms' `` suspension of index arbitrage activity for themselves but -LRB- continuation of -RRB- those activities for customers'' as further reason for the firm to re-evaluate its position. `` If we do decide to re-enter index arbitrage, we will consider limiting our activities to buying on a downtick and attempting to sell on an uptick in the stocks involved,'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said in a statement.
