<HEAD>Congressional Committee Looks at Northrop Payments in Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional subcommittee is trying to determine if $ 6.5 million <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> invested in a hotel project in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was actually intended to influence sales of the company's ill-fated F-20 jet fighter, a committee aide said Thursday. A <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> spokesman denied any violation of the Foreign Corrupt Practices act, and portrayed the company a victim of fraud by its Korean partner in the deal. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> has filed a fraud suit against the Korean company, which was its partner in a 50-50 joint venture to build a hotel in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON>, a spokesman at the company's <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> headquarters. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> never began commercial production of the F-20 because it failed to win sufficient orders. The probe by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on investigations focuses on <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s payment of $ 6.5 million in 1984 to <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> Culture Travel Co.. <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> said the payment was part of a so-called offset program in which the company was to invest in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s economy in return for receiving the fighter Such arrangements are common among aerospace companies dealing with developing countries and are allowed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law. The committee, chaired by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., is probing whether the payment was intended to buy influence rather than build a hotel, said a subcommittee staff member who refused to be identified It would be a violation of the Corrupt Practices Act if the company meant the money as payment to individuals. One aspect of the arrangement that aroused suspicion, the <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> aide said, was that the money intended for the development company was deposited in a <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> bank account. `` We were defrauded by a group of people in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> said. `` We tried and tried again to get that hotel under way and when it became evident that the hotel was n't going to be built we filed for arbitration, and then we filed this suit.'' The suit, filed in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in December 1987, accuses the <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and 12 individuals of defrauding the company. The committee also is probing <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s payment of $ 1.5 million to terminate an agreement with a Korean company that was supposed to help it market the jet in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The committee staff has questioned the size of January 1984 payment to the <ORGANIZATION> Dong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> because the agreement did n't bring any sales, the <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> aide said. <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> declined to comment on the <PERSON> Dong </PERSON> <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> agreement.
