<HEAD>Chrysler Looking to Improve Profits while Holding Market Share</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is looking for ways to improve profits on its auto business without sacrificing sthe market share it gained by holding down prices and offering aggressive buyer incentives, Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> told shareholders Thursday. `` We are in a real dog fight in this market,'' Iacoccasaid. `` We intend to price as aggressively as we have to. Our goal is market share ... We want all the ground we can take.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> increased its share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vehicle market to 14.5 percent at the end of April from 13.3 percent a year ago while industry leader <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> continued to lose market share. The No. 3 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker pushed up its share by keeping its prices the lowest among the Big Three company and offering `` the biggest rebates and incentives the world has ever known,'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said. The pricing strategies and continuing expenses from <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s August acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> have pushed down profits A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> contract ratified last week will put further pressure on earnings. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has increased spending on new product research and development by 25 percent, or $ 150 million, in 1988 _ a necessary expense for updating its cars and trucks with new engines and transmissions in the 1990s. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s immediate capital spending on new products and facilities will be about $ 2.8 billion in 1988, nearly even with $ 3 billion in 1987, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERS