 only a handful of <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> representatives other than President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> _ a member of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s board _ attended the meeting. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, an official with <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 624 at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s New Process Gear plant in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, was assured by <ORGANIZATION> Iacocca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> does not plan to sell any of its <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts subsidiary plants beyond the four already announced _ three in the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> area and one in <LOCATION> Van </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wert </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> wound up in early contract negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> because it entertained a $ 2 billion offer for <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION>, which includes the <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> plant. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> turned down the offer after workers threatened to cripple the company with plant-by-plant strikes. <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> had underestimated `` how strongly our employees felt about remaining part of this <PERSON> Chrysler </PERSON> family.''
