<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet Bjt   05-19 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, Bjt,0663</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks barely broke a two-day losing streak Thursday in a partial recovery that traders attributed to bargain shopping and slightly eased tension over inflation, but the outlook on Wall Street remained bleak. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 56.54 points on Tuesday and Wednesday and dropped another 25 points in early trading, rebounded and finished up 7.63 points to 1,958.72. Broader market indices were mixed. To a large degree, the Dow average's behavior echoed movements in the bond market, which in turn echoed movements in the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> index, a key measure of inflation that tracks commodity futures prices in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The CRB index rose sharply in the morning, heightening inflation fears, raising yields in the bond market and depressing stock prices as bonds became a more attractive alternative to stocks. The CRB index later retreated when soybean futures weakened, easing bond yields and helping the stock market rise. `` The funny thing is how the market is so tuned to inflation, it turned on the commodity price index, which was turned on and off on soybeans,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` This shows how graphically the stock market has become a commodity business,'' <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> said. `` We're subject to the vagaries of traders in the pits of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.'' Some traders said eased yields in the bond market was viewed as a reason by some investors to buy selected well-known stocks that had fallen over the previous two sessions, making them potential bargains. But they said any more indications of higher inflation likely would weaken stocks again. One possibly destabilizing figure was the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer price index for April, to be released Friday morning. `` The market is fragile enough to react very negatively to almost any figure,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthel </PERSON>, strategist for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The market is seeing the bogeyman when it comes to inflation.'' Others said they saw little reason to be optimistic about the market, which has been ignoring signs of economic health that defy the dire predictions issued after the crash seven months ago. `` What we're seeing now are apathetic investors who are using economic news to get out of stock market,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DaPuzzo </PERSON>, manager of retail equities at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The whole thing now is negative psychology.'' Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4-to-3 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 843 down, 640 up and 496 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 165.16 million shares, down from 209.42 million shares in the previous session. Among the most-active blue chip issues, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> fell 2 | to 18 \ after announcing plans to cut its dividend and issue more stock, but other components of the Dow average compensated for Union Carbide's <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> rose 1 -LRB- to 51, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> rose 1 -LCB- to 110 -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> rose | to 23 |, and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> rose 1 to 40 -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Amfac </ORGANIZATION> jumped 6 -RCB- to 45 -LRB- after the company's management offered $ 41 a share to buy it. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> fell -RCB- to 21 -RCB- after chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> told shareholders at their annual meeting that the automaker's second-quarter results probably would n't meet analyst expectations. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 190.26 million shares. The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of 5,000 <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, American and OTC issues, rose by $ 6.48 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> index rose 0.50 to 143.01. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 1.21 to 292.97, and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index rose 1.22 to 252.57. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index fell 1 to 291.79. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market closed at 366.25, down 0.74.
