<SECOND>BC-Brazil-Industry,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Announces New Industrial Liberalization Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> on Thursday announced a plan to remove restrictions on imports and exports, and `` open <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> to international markets.'' The plan ends a decades-old policy of import-substitution, under which the government provided hefty fiscal incentives for companies that produced industrial goods previously found only on international markets. `` Our new industrial policy signals the democratization of Brazilian industry,'' <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> told journalists and government ministers. `` The country's new-found freedom had n't arrived in the industrial or economic sectors, they had n't felt the benefits of our new-found democracy.'' <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said the new measures would cut through thick Brazilian bureaucracy and clarify the government's position in the future. The measures would: _ Free up imports, with some exceptions Imports have been restricted to build the trade surplus and national industry, but now any company can buy most goods on international markets as long it pays hefty import dues. _ Revoke all fiscal incentives for industry, except in the area of technology Companies working in this area can receive tax cuts of up to 8 percent. _ Ease export of industrial goods, with less paperwork and less government control _ Create a five-minister commission to govern industrial policy Details of how the policy was to be implemented were to be worked out at a later date. `` The new policy will modernize <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and open the economy to international markets,'' <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said. Initial business response to the new measures that reversed a 40-year policy of government-led growth was favorable. `` Industry now has clear rules and freedom to grow with less government intervention,'' business leader <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Beer </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globo </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest private network. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> returned to civilian government in March 1985, after 21 years of military rule.
</TEXT>
