<HEAD>Navistar Posts 49 Percent Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strong demand for medium - and heavy-duty trucks boosted <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s second quarter profit by 49 percent from a year earlier, the truck manufacturer said Wednesday <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION> posted net income of $ 70 million, or 24 cents a share, for the three months ended April 30. That compared with a profit of $ 47 million, or 15 cents a share, for the same period a year earlier. Sales increased 13 percent to $ 1.05 billion from $ 930 million in the second quarter of 1987, the Chicago-based manufacturer stated. <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION> said workers at its <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, assembly plant have been working overtime due to strong demand. The company said it would increase its heavy truck production schedules by about 9 percent and its medium-duty truck production rates by 3 percent on Monday, and was exploring other options to further expand production. Increased industrial production and inter-city freight tonnage were important factors in <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION>'s second-quarter performance, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotting </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive, stated. But higher prices for aluminum and steel cut into the company's profit margin, as did production phase-in costs at <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION>'s new foundry in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> and new paint plant in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cotting </PERSON> said Results included a $ 15 million gain from partial recovery of an Australian investment that had previously been written off. In addition, the results included a reduction in the carrying value of the company's investment in <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> preferred stock to $ 105 million from $ 120 million.
